<FIRST>r a PM-SewingSnag     06-10 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sewing Snag,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Labor Department Orders End to Gift Concern's Home Labor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MCCONNELLSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman struggling to keep her $1.7
million gift business alive says the state's enforcement of a law
banning sewing work at home is unfair and has cost nearly 100 women
their jobs.
   The state Department of Labor and Industry has ordered
Overly-Raker Inc. to stop using 100 or more homeworkers to piece
together ``soft sculptures'' _ geese, cows, cats and other creations
stuffed in cloth skins.
   Helen Overly, the company's president, said she was unaware of
the 1937 Industrial Homework Act and made no effort to hide the
company's use of women sewing at home. The law prohibits anyone
other than handicapped or those providing primary care for a
handicapped family member from doing industrial work at home.
   Overly, a former teacher, founded the company in her basement 16
years ago with Freda Raker, a former secretary who handles the
business' creative end.
   Since the Bureau of Labor Standards ordered the company to stop
home production May 11 in response to a complaint, Overly said she
began to hire the 30 or more seamstresses needed at a plant in a
former dairy distribution building in southern Pennsylvania's rural
Fulton County.
   ``The biggest hassle now is to find people who will come in,''
she said.
   Most of the women who had worked at home will lose their jobs
because they have small children or cannot get to the plant, she
said. ``There's a lot of hardship going on because of this.''
   One worker, Virginia Logsdon, said the $250 a month she earned
supplemented her husband's income. She said she worked for almost
two years, usually earning about $4 an hour based on the piece rate
paid by Overly-Raker.
   ``It was very important. It takes what my husband makes to meet
the expenses,'' she said. ``My money would take care of clothes, the
dentist, medicines.''
   Logsdon said she can't leave her 11-year-old daughter, Colletta,
and 12-year-old son, Danny, to drive the more than 100 miles between
her home in rural Armstrong County to the new Overly-Raker plant.
   Helen R. Friedman, director of the labor standards bureau, said
the state was determined to enforce labor laws. ``We work to protect
people's rights,'' she said.
   John Fox, an international vice president for the Amalgamated
Clothing and Textile Workers, said homework provides an opportunity
for companies to exploit workers.
   ``There is no control. There is no such thing as overtime. Their
children help them. Before you know it, children under 12 have
become helpers,'' Fox said. ``It becomes substandard conditions.''
   During a recent interview, Overly said the company had more than
400 orders for more than 8,000 pieces of merchandise as it prepares
for the Halloween to Christmas holiday season.
   She had hired only five full-time seamstresses and was worried
about higher labor costs when the threat from low-cost imports from
Haiti, the Philippines and Taiwan is growing. Still, she said the
company would survive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
