<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan-China     06-10 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Chief Urges Chinese Troops to Support Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan's military chief has urged troops in
China to support the democracy movement and end their crackdown on
demonstrators campaigning for freedom, a television station reported.
   ``We hope the mainland troops, especially the younger ones, will
join the people to fight for freedom and democracy,'' Gen. Hau
Pei-tsun, chief of the armed forces, said Friday night in a rare
interview with the state China Television Co.
   ``We urge troops on the mainland not to become accomplices to the
suppression of democracy,'' Hau said. ``Mainland troops should play
the leading role in establishing a new China under democracy.''
   Hau spoke five days after Chinese troops swept through Beijing's
Tiananman Square, killing hundreds, possibly thousands, to suppress
the pro-democracy uprising that began in mid-April.
   Hardliners in the Chinese leadership appear to have won a power
struggle there, and reports from Beijing say troops now are
arresting supporters of the democracy movement.
   The Nationalists, defeated on the mainland in a civil war in
1949, are technically still at war with the Communists. They
continue to claim they are China's legitimate rulers.
   Hau, 69, born on the mainland and trained in the United States,
heads Taiwan's 500,000-man armed forces.
   Hau said the uprising suggests economic reforms initiated by
senior leader Deng Xiaoping have failed.
   Hau said he now expects a lengthy purge of opponents of China's
hardline leaders.
</TEXT>
