<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-China     06-10 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Hong Kong Preparing to Offer Asylum to Chinese Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong is preparing to offer asylum to political
refugees from China, London's Guardian newspaper reported today.
   Quoting the British colony's secretary for security, the paper
said trained personnel and screening procedures have already been
set up at the border with China's Guandong province, ``even though
it is recognized that this move will add to the growing tensions
between Hong Kong and Beijing.''
   The secretary, Geoffrey Barnes, was in London with Hong Kong's
governor, Sir David Wilson, for talks with the British government.
   ``In the volatile situation in China, nobody can rule out that a
mass of refugees will attempt to cross the thin wire fence that now
divides China from the New Territories,'' the report said.
   The colony consists of an island and a mainland area called the
New Territories adjoining the south of Guandong province.
   In Beijing, Chinese and diplomatic sources say police have begun
arresting intellectuals accused of encouraging the protests and
participants in the resistance to military intervention.
   The Guardian said Barnes stressed that so far there had been no
requests for asylum among the daily handful of Chinese who cross the
border illegally.
   It said that in the past, illegal immigrants were sent back to
China within 24 hours.
   ``But now, in the light of events in China, political asylum will
be granted and, unlike the Vietnamese boat people, whose presence is
causing increasing friction in Hong Kong, Chinese refugees are
certain to be welcomed,'' the report said.
   The military assault on pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing
has hurt the Hong Kong economy by raising anxieties over the period
after July 1997, when Great Britain is to hand the colony back to
China under the terms of an agreement signed in 1984.
   China's upheaval already has dealt a serious blow to the Hong
Kong stock exchange and badly shaken confidence in the property
market.
   Officials in the colony said today they fear a drop in its annual
$4.3 billion tourism business as travelers cancel visits because of
the upheaval.
   About 5.6 million people visited Hong Kong last year and 28
percent of them coupled the trip with a visit to China, according to
the Hong Kong Tourist Association.
   Many people now canceling tours to China also are dropping Hong
Kong, said Manuel Woo, executive director of the Hong Kong Hotels
Association.
</TEXT>
