<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     06-10 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftists Blamed in Killing of Senior Cabinet Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alfredo Cristiani
blamed leftist guerrillas for the assassination of his closest
adviser and said they were ``trying to provoke a reaction'' from his
right-wing government.
   All major political groups condemned the submachine-gun killings
of Jose Antonio Rodriguez Porth, 73, and two bodyguards Friday
outside the minister's home.
   President Bush issued a White House statement calling the
assassination a ``vicious murder,'' and some Salvadoran politicans
warned it could lead to new political polarization in the nation.
   Rodriguez Porth, a Cabinet member considered Christiani's chief
of staff, was the highest ranking official killed in the 9-year-old
civil war between the U.S.-backed government and the rebels. The
rebels as of early today had not claimed responsibility for the
shootings.
   Guillermo Ungo, a Social Democrat and political ally of the
rebels, said the slaying was ``an assasination in cold blood ...
that does not contribute in any way to peaceful coexistence and
dialogue.''
   Cristiani called Rodriguez ``one of the most illustrious men of
our country'' and told a news conference his adminstration will not
not allow more ``provocations that push our country farther down
into the whirlpool of violence.''
   Cristiani said his government is convinced the leftist Farabundo
Marti Liberation Front (FMLN) is ``trying to provoke a reaction from
us, but we are not going to react outside of the law.''
   Gunmen fired on Rodriguez Porth's car after he left his home in
the capital. He died shortly after he was taken at Zaldivar
Hospital, a nurse said on condition of anonymity. Police said the
two bodyguards, one of whom was driving the car, died at the scene.
   Gerardo Le Chevallier, leader of the centrist Christian
Democratic Party, warned the assassinations could mark a new
political polarization in the country.
   He said the attack was the result of ``the declarations of
Cristiani that if the FMLN does not accept its peace proposal there
could be a military response.''
   The rebel front last week offered to halt attacks if the new
right-wing Republican Nationalist Alliance government eliminated
death squads. The alliance, known as Arena, denies any involvement
with death squads and spurned the proposal.
   Arena was founded in 1981 by cashiered army Maj. Roberto
d'Aubuisson, who has been linked to the squads that killed thousands
of suspected leftists in the early 1980's. He denies the accusations.
   Also among the founders was Rodriguez, who was a vice minister in
the 1940's, a member of the civilian-military junta in 1961 and
foreign minister in 1978.
   Guerrillas have pledged to make the country ungovernable under
the administration of Cristiani, who won a presidential election in
March.
   About 70,000 people, mostly civilians, have died since civil war
broke out in 1980.
</TEXT>
