<FIRST>r a PM-ForcedRepatriation 1stLd-Writethru a0413 06-10 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forced Repatriation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0413,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diverse Groups Protest Proposed Indochinese Immigration Measures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ed: Leads with 3 grafs to recast and explain allusion to `Voyage
of the Damned.' Picks up 4th graf: `A spokesman ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters rallied against the proposed
forced repatriation of Indochinese refugees from Hong Kong, likening
the move to the Voyage of the Damned in 1939.
   They demonstrated outside the British Consulate in San Francisco
on Friday as officials in London urged that Hong Kong send home most
Vietnamese boat people.
   Demonstrators harkened back to the voyage of a German ship loaded
with fleeing Jews who were refused entrance to the United States.
The 900 Jewish passengers aboard the SS St. Louis returned to
various European ports and many later died at Nazi hands. The event
was depicted in the 1975 movie ``Voyage of the Damned'' starring
Faye Dunaway and Max von Sydow.
   A spokesman at San Francisco's British Consulate said officials
had no comment. But the colony's British secretary of security,
Geoffrey Barnes, told reporters at a London news conference that
Hong Kong ``has had enough.''
   The refugee problem is creating a second crisis for the British
colony deeply worried about coming under Chinese rule in 1997, he
said.
   Hong Kong has 42,766 Vietnamese boat people, one-third of whom
arrived this year. Barnes said all but 14,150 were simply seeking a
better way of life, rather than political refuge.
   The protesters _ including Jewish representatives, Democratic
lawmakers and former Vietnamese boat people _ carried signs that
read, ``Princess Diana. Don't Let Them Butcher Us'' or that quoted
Margaret Thatcher: ``When people are free to choose, they choose to
be free.''
   Dr. Toan Truong, who escaped from Vietnam just two days before
the fall of Saigon in April 1975, told some 50 rally participants
that forced repatriation was ``something that will be perpetrated by
bloodless bureaucrats.''
   ``This is a crime against humanity,'' said Truong, who was among
two dozen protesters who began a five-day fast to call attention to
their cause.
   Besides the British colony, protesters said countries that may be
considering repatriation include Brunei, Malayasia, Indonesia,
Singapore and Thailand.
   Demonstrators called on Britain to oppose repatriation and the
screening of Southeast Asian immigrants. The issues will be
discussed at the two-day International Conference on Indochinese
Refugees in Geneva beginning Tuesday.
</TEXT>
