<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos-Suit     06-10 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos-Suit,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Seek Judgment Against Marcos Even in Event of Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors want to guarantee they have a
claim against the assets of former Philippines President Ferdinand
E. Marcos even after he's dead.
   To that end, they filed a civil racketeering lawsuit against
Marcos and his wife, Imelda, on Friday.
   The critically ill, 71-year-old Marcos and his 59-year-old wife
are already under a criminal racketeering indictment in New York,
charged with siphoning millions of dollars from their homeland's
treasury.
   The latest lawsuit, filed under the civil aspects of the
Racketeer Influenced Corrupt Organizations Act, closely parallels
allegations in the 90-count criminal indictment.
   ``The civil complaint was filed in order to ensure that the
interests of the United States as well as the interests of the
victims of the racketeering enterprise will be fully preserved in
the event of the death of Ferdinand E. Marcos,'' said U.S. Attorney
Benito Romano.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles LaBella said the victims include
the Philippine people and numerous U.S. banks.
   The criminal charges against Marcos and attending forfeiture
claims against his alleged ill-gotten gains would be dismissed after
his death, Romano explained. ``Conversely, a civil complaint filed
by the government against an individual defendant continues against
the estate of a deceased defendant,'' he said.
   Marcos' lawyer, Richard A. Hibey, in Washington, D.C., said he
would fight the civil case as well as the criminal charges.
   John J. Tigue, a New York attorney for Mrs. Marcos, said: ``The
lawsuit will be defended against vigorously, as is the underlying
charge which essentially contains the same allegations.''
   The Marcoses have lived in exile in Hawaii since they were
toppled in a popular uprising in February 1986.
   Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent to the federal charges. Her
husband's ill health kept him from making the trip from Hawaii to
New York for arraignment. In April he was separated from the case,
although the charges were not dropped.
   Marcos, who suffers from heart and lung ailments, has been
hospitalized in Honolulu's St. Francis Medical Center since Jan. 16.
He underwent emergency surgery for kidney failure last month.
   His doctors and lawyers say he is near death.
   A U.S. grand jury indicted the Marcoses and eight others last
October on various charges. Racketeering charges against the
Marcoses accused them of looting more than $103 million from the
Philippines to buy art and real estate in New York City.
   The indictment also said the Marcoses defrauded U.S. banks and
lending institutions of more than $165 million in buying and
financing the choice Manhattan real estate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
