<FIRST>r i PM-Honduras-Panama     06-10 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Panama,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduras Warns Panama it Will Cut Electricity if Bills Not Paid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras says it will cut the
electricity it provides to Panama if its Central American's neighbor
does not pay a $4.2 million bill due since 1987.
   Reginaldo Panting, secretary of Economy and Commerce, told a news
conference on Friday that ``our position is not to pressure the
Panamanian government nor the chief of the Defense Forces, Gen.
Antonio Noriega.
   ``We are only trying to get pending bills paid ... and Panama has
a bill with Honduras it has to pay,'' Panting said.
   Honduras provides Panama with about 10 percent of its electrical
service. Honduras has the largest electrical processing plant in
Central America and also sells electricity to neighboring Nicaragua.
   Panting said he traveled to Panama two months ago ``to remind the
government of its debt with Honduras.
   ``At the time, we warned that we could suspend the energy at the
end of the month if Panama doesn't immediately proceed to pay the
debt, but it hasn't done it.''
   He said Panama had discussed the possibility of repaying the debt
with sugar exports to Honduras but has not done so.
   ``Faced with what has happened, we are left with one other
option: cut the electricity we send to Honduras,'' Panting said.
   He said he will travel to Panama again next week in a last
attempt to resolve the problem.
   Noriega is considered Panama's de facto leader. He was indicted
by two Florida grand juries in 1988 on drug trafficking charges, and
the United States has placed economic sanctions on the nation in
effort to force him to step down.
</TEXT>
