<FIRST>r a PM-China-USRallies     06-10 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-US Rallies,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Rally in U.S. To Support Chinese Student Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BX1, NY6</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans and Chinese across the country rallied, rang bells and
held candlelight vigils to keep the flame of pro-democracy sentiment
burning despite the brutal crackdown in China.
   ``We don't want people to think that because it is quiet over
there, all is over,'' J.D. Kuo, a Chinese-American research
scientist with G.D. Searle, told about 1,500 people at a downtown
Chicago rally Friday. ``By adding our voices, the students in
Beijing will know people are behind them.''
   Church bells rang throughout Chicago after a moment of silence,
and in New York's Chinatown, more than 5,000 people attended a
memorial service followed by a mock funeral procession for the
victims of the Beijing massacre.
   Marchers carried a figure inspired by the Statue of Liberty,
similar to one displayed by the student protesters in Tiananmen
Square until it was destroyed last weekend.
   ``This has united the Chinese people for one cause _ to overthrow
the government and establish democracy,'' said Peter Lee, one of the
student organizers of the memorial service. ``We must never allow
them to crush another body.''
   Later, more than 15,000 people packed Dag Hammarskjold Plaza
across from the United Nations, many wearing white headbands bearing
the word ``freedom.''
   Mayor Edward I. Koch drew cheers when he said, ``All these
students wanted was a chance to speak with their own government
about democracy.'' Koch also promised to rename the corner outside
the Chinese Consulate as Tiananmen Square.
   Under a cold drizzle late Friday, about 100 Chinese students
gathered by candlelight on the steps of Boston's City Hall to lay a
wreath in honor of their fallen comrades back home.
   ``I wish there was more we could do, but at this moment we just
don't know what to do,'' said Yong Lee, a 28-year-old graduate
student at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``We're all
very deeply, deeply sad and shocked.''
   Earlier, a rally by University of Massachusetts students in
Northampton was joined by Kui Xu, a graduate student and
granddaughter of former Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang, whose
death on April 15 ignited the pro-democracy movement.
   Students facing final examinations took time out on other
campuses to remember their slain peers in Beijing.
   In Los Angeles, Hispanic students helped Asian-Americans organize
an afternoon march, and friends circulated petitions on behalf of
Tong Bonning, a University of California, Los Angeles, graduate
mathematics exchange student who is missing after returning home
with donations for pro-democracy protestors.
   Chinese students at Princeton University in New Jersey held a
memorial service, and at the University of Pittsburgh, students
opened a multimedia exhibit tracking the pro-democracy movement in
China.
   At the University of California, San Diego, about 150 Chinese and
American students sang John Lennon's ``Imagine'' and other peace
anthems at a mournful noon gathering.
   Sorrow abounded over the Chinese repression of the pro-democracy
movement.
   ``We thought maybe the government was going to change,'' said
S.Y. Cheng, a University of California, Los Angeles, professor
originally from Hong Kong. ``Sometimes I think all of us are too
naive.''
   ``They shouldn't give up. They should continue. They don't fear
dying,'' Zhewu Wang, 31, a visiting scholar at the University of
Iowa from the northeast China city of Harbin, said in Iowa City.
</TEXT>
