<HEAD>Eastern Seaboard Soaked By Lingering Storms; Winds Buffet Parts of
Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Lingering storms drenched much of the eastern seaboard this
morning and strong winds buffeted areas in Florida after a fatal
tornado whipped through Philadelphia.
   Thunderstorm winds gusted to 53 mph at Desert Rock, Nev. In New
Mexico, Lake Arthur, near Roswell, was struck by golfball-size hail.
   Fierce thunderstorm winds caused damage at Buckhead Ridge, Fla.,
about 50 miles northwest of Palm Beach.
   Elsewhere, the thunderstorms spawned locally heavy rains. Flood
watches were posted early today in southeast New York, southern New
England and northern New Jersey. Flood watches also were posted in
western Oklahoma.
   Showers and occasional thunderstorms lingered through New
England, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania and northern West
Virginia early this morning.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered in south-central
Texas, northern Texas across eastern New Mexico, Oklahoma, western
Arkansas, Kansas, Colorado, south-central Nebraska, Utah, Nevada and
from western Montana across eastern Washington.
   On Friday night, a tornado packing heavy rains and winds up to
120 mph struck Philadelphia, leaving one person dead and one
injured, after damaging homes and cars and ripping up trees.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT included
2 inches at Islip, N.Y., almost 2 inches at New York City, and
nearly 1{ inches at Chicopee Falls, Mass.
   Clear skies and light winds sent temperatures dipping over the
upper Mississippi Valley and frost advisories were posted today in
northwest Wisconsin and eastern Minnesota.
   Today's forecast called for rain in much of New England, New York
and western Pennsylvania; and showers and thunderstorms from Montana
across Wyoming, western South Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, western
Missouri and north-central Texas.
   Predicted highs: 50s and 60s in much of New England; 60s from
upper Michigan across Wisconsin, and along California's southern
coast; 90s in Florida, the central Gulf of Mexico coast, much of
Louisiana, southern Texas and southern New Mexico, and the inland
part of central and southern California; 90s to near 105 degrees
across the desert Southwest; and 70s and 80s in the rest of the
nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Hibbing, Minn., to 85 at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 66 fair; Boston 54 rain; Buffalo 61 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 75 fair; Cincinnati 60 fair; Cleveland 61 foggy;
Detroit 57 cloudy; Miami 81 partly cloudy; Philadelphia 71 foggy;
Pittsburgh 61 fair; Portland, Maine 51 rain; Washington 70 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 51 fair; Chicago 59 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
71 partly cloudy; Denver 55 partly cloudy; Des Moines 52 partly
cloudy; Indianapolis 54 fair; Kansas City 62 partly cloudy;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 53 fair; Nashville 67 fair; New Orleans 74
foggy; St. Louis 60 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 64 windy; Anchorage 50 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 83 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 61 cloudy; Phoenix 85 fair; Salt
Lake City 60 cloudy; San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 54 partly
cloudy; Seattle 53 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 57 rain; Toronto 59 fair.
