<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-10 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The yellow brick road leads to Holland this
weekend, as four of the original munchkins join fans of ``The Wizard
of Oz.''
   Many believe the author who inspired the film classic, L. Frank
Baum, patterned part of Dorothy's travels to Oz after local sites
and people because he had a summer cottage in this town.
   ``It really reminds me of the set,'' said Margaret Pellegrini,
65, who played one of the ``Sleepyheads'' who welcomed Dorothy to Oz.
   Dorothy apparently was modeled after a neighbor, Dorothy
Martindale, who wore her hair in pigtails and had a small dog, said
festival organizer J.L. Landry. The Emerald Castle is said to be
drawn from nearby Castle Park and a circle of houses called Perry
Circle was the model for Munchkinland, she said.
   This year _ the 50th anniversary of the MGM classic _ will be
especially busy, said Meinhardt Raabe, who played the coroner who
pronounced the Wicked Witch of the East dead after she was crushed
by Dorothy's house.
   Former munchkins Ruth Duccini and Mary Ellen St. Aubin also
appear at the festival, which runs through Sunday in this
southwestern community near Lake Michigan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FABIUS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's no bull that state Sen. Nancy Larraine
Hoffmann owns a stud that was named after the state's governor.
   Actually, Cuomo is a bull _ all 800 pounds of him.
   Cuomo's odyssey began at the New York State Fair two years ago,
when 4H'er Trista House of Parish, N.Y., won the showmanship ribbon
in the junior division for her cow, Phoebe.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo presented her with the blue ribbon and House was
so moved she decided to name Phoebe's first son after the state's
favorite son.
   Two months ago, Hoffmann was shopping for a breeding bull and
bought Cuomo, unaware of the stud's name.
   ``As soon as we heard, we said, `Oh, no,''' said Hoffmann, a
Democrat. She thought the name would be disrespectful of the
governor, also a Democrat.
   In the end, she decided to steer away from calling the animal
after the governor and changed the bovine's name to Bubba.
</TEXT>
