<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0652EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats     06-10 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Affidavit Alleges Illegal Waste Burning at Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDY SHORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant
dumped toxic chemicals into creeks that lead to water supplies for
four Denver suburbs and illegally burned hazardous wastes at the
site, according to an FBI affidavit.
   Both the Department of Energy, which owns the plant, and Rockwell
International Corp., which operates it, covered up the contamination
by stating that the plant was in compliance with environmental laws
and regulations, the affidavit alleged.
   U.S. Magistrate Hilbert Schauer unsealed the affidavit Friday
after a newspaper challenged withholding of the information that led
Schauer to issue a search warrant for a raid on the plant Tuesday by
federal agents.
   The plant, which processes plutonium for nuclear weapons, is 16
miles northwest of Denver.
   The 116-page affidavit indicates the Justice Department
investigation into possible criminal violations of hazardous waste
laws will focus on activities going back to November 1980.
   The affidavit also questions the DOE's decision to award an $8.6
million bonus to Rockwell for excellent management of Rocky Flats.
   The Rocky Mountain News reported in Friday's editions that the
General Accounting Office also has launched an investigation of
performance bonuses awarded Rocky Flats' managers.
   The GAO probe was the third blow sustained by the facility this
week.
   On Tuesday, 75 FBI and Environmental Protection Agency agents
raided Rocky Flats in a move dubbed ``Operation Desert Glow,'' as
part of the Justice Department inquiry. On Wednesday, the Colorado
Department of Health announced it had found 25 environmental
violations at the plant.
   ``We need to check out every allegation that is in this
document,'' Gov. Roy Romer said of the affidavit. ``If it (the
plant) can't meet criteria for health and safety, we close it down.''
   The affidavit revealed that FBI aerial infrared surveillance of
the plant in December found that an incinerator in a plutonium
reprocessing building that was closed for safety violations was
being illegally operated.
   The DOE closed the building in October after an outside warning
sign was accidently covered up, and three DOE inspectors walked in
without protective garb. The building reopened in January.
   The affidavit also alleged that since 1986, Rocky Flats has
generated ``at least 35 to 40 hazardous or mixed wastes sent for
final disposal to various on-site facilities'' that do not have
permits or interim status under the 1976 Resource Conservation and
Recovery Act.
   ``The knowing treatment, storage and disposal of hazardous or
mixed wastes without a permit ... is an RCRA felony,'' the affidavit
said.
   The illegal discharge of pollutants into Walnut Creek occurred
Nov. 15 and 16, the affidavit alleged, adding that the discharges
and subsequent efforts to conceal them violated the Clean Water Act.
Walnut Creek drains into the reservoir for Broomfield, a city of
27,600 residents 10 miles north of Denver.
   The FBI also detected liquid discharges into Woman Creek, which
flows into the lake supplying water to the cities of Westminster,
Northglenn and Thornton, just north of Denver, which have a combined
population of about 157,000.
   Testing of the creeks ``strongly suggests that the contamination
is medical waste originating from a research laboratory or a
pharmacy'' at Rocky Flats, the affidavit said.
   The affidavit went on to say that there was probable cause to
believe Rockwell and DOE officials in November 1985 falsely
certified that Rocky Flats was in compliance with all applicable
groundwater monitoring requirements under the RCRA.
   ``In fact, various Rockwell and DOE officials were aware of
serious contamination and were informed that the monitoring system
was deficient and did not comply with the RCRA,'' the affidavit said.
   Chris Sankey, a DOE spokeswoman in Washington, said agency
officials had not had time to study the affidavit and had no
comment. She also said she was unaware of the GAO investigation.
   In a news release, the department said a special DOE
investigation team has been at Rocky Flats since June 6, but has not
found ``any condition or situation which presents an imminent danger
to the public's health or safety.''
   Dennis Hurtt, a Rockwell spokesman in Denver, declined to comment
Friday. He said Rockwell attorneys were reviewing the affidavit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890610-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0817EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-AmericanPOWs     06-10 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-American POWs,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. to Interview Japanese Monk About American POWs in Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American military attache will interview a
Japanese monk who has reportedly said he saw American prisoners in
the re-education camp where he was held in Vietnam, a U.S. Embassy
spokesman said today.
   The monk's daughter quoted her father as saying he shared a cell
with three American prisoners for the last six years he spent in
captivity. She said her father did not remember their names but
described them as young and healthy.
   The monk, Iwanobu Yoshida, 65, reportedly suffers from mental
disorders and a speech impediment. He has been hospitalized since
January when he returned to Japan after being released from 14 years
of imprisonment in Vietnam.
   In the past week he has given his first interviews to the
Japanese media, raising interest with claims he saw Americans held
since the Vietnam War.
   Vietnam denies holding American prisoners, and recently it has
cooperated with U.S. officials searching for remains of Americans
missing in action.
   Yoshida's daughter, Keiko Takatsuka, told The Associated Press
today that her father communicated with the Americans in his cell
through gestures.
   ``My father told me that when he asked them if they were
Americans, they nodded,'' Ms. Takatsuka said during a telephone
interview from her home in Sapporo on Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost
island. She said the prisoners were not allowed to speak to each
other.
   Her report differed from one earlier in the week on the Kyodo
News Service in which Yoshida was quoted as saying he saw ``five or
six'' American POWs but never spoke with them and had been held
apart from them. The location of the re-education camp has not been
disclosed.
   Ms. Takatsuka told AP the Kyodo reporter must have misunderstood
because her father told her several times he had been held with the
Americans.
   A U.S. military attache will travel to Sapporo on Sunday to
interview Yoshida, a U.S. Embassy spokesman said, speaking
anonymously.
   He said Ms. Takatsuka met with a U.S. Navy attache at the U.S.
Embassy in Tokyo recently to report on her father's remarks and that
the information was forwarded to Washington for analysis.
   Ms. Takatsuka initially refused to speak with U.S. officials,
saying her father was too ill, according to the embassy spokesman.
   Yoshida suffers from mental disorders and a speech impediment,
said Hidenori Hareyama, a spokesman for Shiraishi Tokushukai
Hospital on Hokkaido where Yoshida is being treated.
   Only Yoshida's daughter can understand what he says and his
speech is at times incoherent, Hareyama said. He refused to
elaborate.
   Yoshida, a Buddhist monk, told the Kyodo News Service that
Vietnamese political prisoners also called the foreigners in the
camp Americans.
   Ms. Takatsuka said her father does not remember the names of the
three held in his cell but said they were still ``young and
healthy.''
   Yoshida told her he saw more American POWs, perhaps more than 10,
before he suffered a stroke three years ago. ``My father is still
afraid somebody will come and get him to throw him back in the
Vietnamese prison,'' she said.
   Yoshida, formerly a city councilman in Mibari on Hokkaido, became
a monk in 1966 and emigrated to Vietnam, where he set up a temple in
Saigon, now called Ho Chi Minh City. He was granted South Vietnamese
citizenship in 1973, then was arrested in 1975 after the takeover of
South Vietnam by communist forces.
   On Jan. 20, Vietnam released Yoshida for humanitarian reasons
after appeals by international human rights groups including Amnesty
International.
   A total of 1,730 Americans are listed as missing in action in
Vietnam, and 634 are missing in Cambodia, Laos and China, according
to U.S. figures.
   The Indochina war ended in 1975 with communist victories over
U.S.-supported governments in Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890610-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0415 06-10 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Dead as Syrians Shell Christian Coastline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 5 grafs after 11th pvs, ``Details were...'' to UPDATE
with envoys arriving in Baghdad, add comment. Pickup 12th pvs, ``The plan...''
TRIMS.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners shelled the coast north of
Beirut today, killing four people and wounding six, as an Arab envoy
tried to halt 12 weeks of bloodshed between Syrian and Christian
forces.
   A police spokesman said about 200 shells and rockets fired from
Syrian batteries in Moslem west Beirut exploded around the Christian
ports of Jounieh and Byblos early in the day.
   He said the fatalities were ``civilians killed near Jounieh when
a 107mm Katyusha rocket hit a residential district near the harbor.''
   The latest casualties brought the overall toll to 367 people
killed and 1,427 wounded since the current round of violence broke
out March 8 between Aoun's Christian army units and an alliance of
Syrian-Druse forces.
   The escalation coincided with the arrival in Beirut of Lakhdar
Ibrahimi, assistant Arab League secretary general, in a renewed
effort to stabilize a cease-fire.
   Ibrahimi, an Algerian, crossed Beirut's dividing Green Line for
talks with Aoun at the general's bunker office under the
bomb-ravaged presidential palace of Baabda, east of the capital.
   Ibrahimi drove to Moslem west Beirut from Damascus, the Syrian
capital, Friday and held separate meetings with Salim Hoss, who
heads the Moslem Cabinet in the nation's dual government, and
Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini.
   The Arab envoy was dispatched to Lebanon by the leaders of
Morocco, Saudi Arabia and Algeria to seek compliance with a
cease-fire called May 26. The committee of three Arab League heads
of state was formed to find a solution to the 14-year civil war
within six months.
   The three leaders also sent their foreign ministers on a tour of
Syria, Iraq and the five permanent member states of the U.N.
Security Council to promote a proposed settlement for the Lebanese
crisis.
   The ministers _ Prince Saud Al-Faisal of Saudi Arabia, Abdel
Latif Al-Filali of Morocco and Bouallam Bsayeh of Algeria _ held a
second, six-hour meeting Friday with Syrian President Hafez Assad in
Damascus.
   Details of the discussions were not officially disclosed.
   The three foreign ministers today arrived in Baghdad, where they
were greeted by foreign minister Tariq Aziz.
   Al-Filali told reporters: ``We are sure we will find complete
cooperation from Iraqi officials in trying to find a solution to the
Lebanese crisis.''
   Before leaving Syria, the Algerian foreign minister said, ``We
tried in Damascus to define the major subjects that could be
achieved in the forseeable future.'' He said that ``the solution is,
in the end, in the hands of the Lebanese, and we were able to see
Damascus' willingness to help Lebanon.''
   The independent Beirut daily paper An-Nahar said the three were
soliciting support for a seven-point settlement proposal.
   The plan, according to the paper, calls for ``exerting
international pressure on Israel to withdraw its forces from south
Lebanon.''
   It also proposes the ``deployment of an Algerian force'' along a
75-mile stretch of Lebanon's Mediterranean coast to prevent the
import and export of illegal material at the various ports.
   The coastal strip referred to in the plan extends from just above
the southern provincial capital of Sidon, through Beirut, to the
northern city of Tripoli.
   The scenario also calls for ``lifting all sea, land and air
blockades, reopening blocked roads between the sectors, including
the Beirut-Damascus highway'' that runs across sections of Lebanon
controlled by warring Christian and Druse militias, the paper said.
   It said Arab military observers would be deployed at the
crossings and along the Beirut-Damascus highway.
   The plan also calls for ``convening a session of the Lebanese
parliament to consider a draft for political reforms and the
election by parliament of a president who would pledge to implement
the reforms.''
   The last point in the plan calls for ``discussing the question of
Syrian withdrawal from Lebanon.''
   Israel controls a 6-to-10-mile deep strip of Lebanese territory
along their border. It serves as a buffer against cross-border
guerrilla attacks.
</TEXT>
