<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Jaruzelski 1stLd-Writethru a0422 06-10 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Jaruzelski, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0422,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland's Communist Leader Visits Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with protest. Pickup 7th graf
pvs, ``Jarulzelski said...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Wojciech Jaruzelski says the
Communist Party's resounding defeat in Poland's freest postwar
elections may have been only a passing phenomenon.
   At the Polish Embassy in London today, a small group of Polish
emigres protested Gen. Jaruzelski's visit, with one banner
declaring: ``From Poland to Peking, communism brings death.''
   Jaruzelski arrived in London today after a one-day visit to
Belgium, and he met for 25 minutes with Foreign Secretary Sir
Geoffrey Howe at Heathrow Airport.
   In Belgium, Jaruzelski said the election results were ``a
reflection not only of the attitudes but also of the emotions of the
Polish people.''
   ``But as you know, emotions are sometimes ephemeral,'' he said in
an interview in Brussels with the British Broadcasting Corp. He
spoke in Polish, and his remarks were translated.
   Following a stop to lay a wreath at Polish war graves in England
today, the Communist Party leader was to meet with Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher for lunch at her country estate, Chequers. He
plans to return to Poland on Sunday.
   Members of Solidarity with Solidarity, a British-based group,
organized their weekend vigil outside the embassy near a separate
weeklong vigil outside the Chinese Embassy.
   ``We are not saying that what happened in Poland was as bad as
the Chinese massacres,'' said protest organizer Barbara Rudewicz,
referring to the Chinese army's attacks on pro-democracy protesters
a week ago. ``But in 1981, it was Gen. Jaruzelski who brought out
the tanks onto the streets of Poland, when several hundred people
were killed during martial law.''
   Solidarity was crushed at that time and later banned. It was
legalized under an April pact with the government.
   In a statement released Friday, Solidarity with Solidarity
described Jaruzelski as ``a man decisively rejected by his nation''
in Sunday's elections.
   In the Polish voting for the new 100-seat Senate, Solidarity won
92 seats and the other eight were undecided. Independent candidates
were allowed to run for only 161 seats in the existing 460-seat
Sejm, or lower house, but they won 160 of them.
   Only two of 35 top Communist Party leaders and their allies
running on a special list of unopposed candidates gained a majority
of ``yes'' votes, allowing them to take seats without a new election.
   Jaruzelski said in a British newspaper interview this week that
he would stand by the results and suggested that his Communist Party
could lose power in totally free elections in 1993.
   In the BBC interview, Jaruzelski said the elections were not a
``football match ... it is a political process.''
   He referred ruefully to his imposition of martial law in Poland
in 1981 and his banning of the free trade union Solidarity.
   ``Sometimes it takes a long time before the revolution becomes
civilized,'' said Jaruzelski. ``We could not avoid it either.''
   Mrs. Thatcher invited Jaruzelski to Britain after she visited
Poland last November and met with both government and Solidarity
leaders.
   British officials said the prime minister was interested in
talking with Jaruzelski about the elections and his plans for the
future.
   Jaruzelski's visit is part of widening contacts between Poland
and Western government leaders, who have welcomed the Polish reforms.
   French President Francois Mitterrand will visit Poland next week
and President Bush is due to go there July 9-11.
</TEXT>
