<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Protests 1stLd-Writethru a0426 06-10 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Battle Students, Arrest 1,000</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 1,000 arrests, new clashes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students today
battled police with firebombs, rocks and clubs after protesters
demanded the Seoul government let them take part in a youth festival
in communist North Korea.
   Police reported more than 1,000 arrests.
   About 2,000 students fought riot police at two campuses in Seoul
after they were blocked from marching into the streets to denounce
President Roh Tae-woo's government and the United States. Thirty
student leaders were seized trying to reach the North Korean border
for talks with communist officials, police said.
   About 1,500 students fought police with iron pipes, clubs and
rocks at Yonsei University and about 500 students threw firebombs
and rocks at police at nearby Sogang University. Police hurled rocks
back at students but did not use tear gas.
   ``Crush the Roh Tae-woo regime!'' and ``Yankee go home!''
students yelled.
   Hundreds of students later battled police in central Seoul,
hurling rocks and bricks. Riot squads used tear gas to break up the
protesters and chased the students through the streets. Shoppers and
pedestrians fled for cover.
   Troops and students were injured in the fighting, but the police
had no figures on casualties.
   More than 1,000 students were arrested in the clashes or as they
tried to reach the universities to take part in a second day of
protests, police said.
   Police officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
20,000 riot police were deployed in Seoul to block the university
demonstrations. About 6,000 troopers in green combat fatigues and
visored helmets ringed Yonsei and Sogang, outnumbering the
demonstrators.
   The protests came after students staged rallies at the two
colleges to demand to take part in the 13th World Youth Festival
next month in the North Korean capital of Pyongyang. Radical
students are calling for unification with the communist North.
   North Korea has invited South Korean students to attend the youth
festival, an athletic and cultural festival attended mainly by
non-aligned and communist nations. South Korea has accused the North
of attempting to incite domestic unrest to weaken the Seoul
government.
   Student leaders charge that Roh and the United States keep the
Korean peninsula divided. They have called for the overthrow of Roh
and expulsion of the 43,000 U.S. troops based in South Korea.
   The two Koreas are bitter rivals. They have clashed frequently
over the years. North Korea invaded the south in 1950 to start the
Korean War.
   Radical students and dissidents have been calling for the fall of
the Roh government, but they lack support because of their extreme
views and violent tactics.
</TEXT>
