<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan     06-10 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Sentenced to Death by Stoning for Adultery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHAIRPUR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lower court today convicted six
people of adultery and sentenced them to death by stoning under an
Islamic law.
   Judge Mirza Saeed Beg invoked the controversial ``Hadood
Ordinance'' enacted in 1979 by former President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq.
   It was the first such ruling since Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto
came to power in December. The U.S.-eductated Ms. Bhutto has pledged
to press for repeal of the Islamic law, which imposes harsh
punishment for moral offenses and limits women's rights.
   Beg's court convicted Ghulam Qadir Sher and Noor Khatoon of
marrying illegally because Ms. Khatoon failed to secure a proper
divorce from her previous husband, Shaikh Anver Ali Sher.
   The court found four of Qadir Sher's friends guilty as
accomplices for helping arrange his marriage with Ms. Khatoon.
   No date was set for the executions. Members of the Khatoon and
Qadir Sher families said they would appeal to a Sindh province high
court.
   Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning Pakistan People's Party has called for
the repeal of all discriminatory Islamic laws promulgated under
Zia's 11-year rule.
   As chief of the army, Gen. Zia toppled Ms. Bhutto's father, Prime
Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in a 1977 military coup and had him
executed two years later. Zia died in a plane crash in August. An
inquiry found the plane was downed by saboteurs but was unable to
identify them.
   Repeal of the laws passed under Zia would require majorities in
both houses of Parliament. Ms. Bhutto's sizeable right-wing
opposition has said it will block any government move against the
Islamic ordinances.
</TEXT>
