<SECOND>PM-Severe Storm, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0421,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Storm Spawns Philadelphia Tornado; 1 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The body...', to UPDATE with identity of victim,
CORRECT her age to 13 sted 15.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm slammed Philadelphia with heavy rain,
winds up to 120 mph and a tornado, disrupting power to thousands of
customers and leaving one person dead and one seriously injured.
   A suspected tornado in Delaware's New Castle County, across the
state line southeast of Philadelphia, destroyed at least one house
and a school gymnasium, damaged at least four other homes and
knocked out power to about 1,000 customers Friday evening,
authorities said. No injuries were reported.
   The twister landed in Philadelphia's affluent Society Hill
section about 7:15 p.m. and slashed northeast for half a mile to the
Delaware River, the National Weather Service said.
   Police and witnesses said the funnel cloud then skipped across
the river and damaged a dozen houses in Camden, N.J. The weather
service said it had not investigated the Camden damage and could not
confirm a tornado there.
   The body of girl who apparently fell into a rain-swollen
tributary of Cobbs Creek in suburban Upper Darby during the storm
was found two miles downstream late Friday, said Upper Darby
Township Detective Ron Lavin. The victim was identified today as
13-year-old Alix Christina Lidle of Upper Darby.
   Police said a man was blown into a Society Hill telephone booth.
He was listed in stable but guarded condition with a head injury
early today in the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania.
   The north and west walls of a three-story parking garage
collapsed during the storm, damaging two parked vehicles and a
nearby house, police said.
   Officer Michael Beren said a sudden darkness descended while he
was on patrol.
   ``I couldn't see two feet in front of my face,'' he said. ``It
was black and dark _ and then there was a roar.''
   The tornado was 50 yards wide at points, the weather service said.
   Philadelphia Electric Co. spokesman Michael Wood said about 4,500
customers lost power for at least part of the evening.
   A Camden family had to be evacuated from their home after a beam
crashed through the ceiling, said Camy Trinidad, a spokeswoman for
the Camden County Red Cross.
</TEXT>
