<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 1046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Politics     06-10 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Proposes Sharp Reductions In Soviet Bureaucracy</HEAD>
<UNK>By ANDREW KATELL ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov today proposed sharp
reductions in the vast Soviet bureaucracy and said the remaining
government ministries should turn many of their powers over to the
nation's 15 republics.
   Speaking to a joint session of the bicameral Supreme Soviet _ a
new 542-member, full-time legislature _ Ryzhkov said that of the 50
government ministries handling basic elements of the economy _
construction, transportation, agriculture and defense _ only 32
would remain.
   In addition, he told the lawmakers in a session broadcast live on
radio and television that the number of members of the Council of
Ministers, or Cabinet that he heads, will be slashed from 100 to 10.
   The proposals, which the legislature is to vote on later this
month, mark another step in President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
attempts to streamline the Soviet bureaucracy he has blamed for
impeding his economic reforms. They would also transfer many
economic management functions to the 15 Soviet republics, many of
which are campaigning for greater control over their affairs.
   Ryzhkov, the 59-year-old technocrat re-elected premier on
Wednesday, said the remaining ministries in Moscow will focus on
long-range planning and on scientific and technological help in the
spheres they oversee. The ministries would leave the day-to-day
managment they now provide to the republics.
   At the same time, two special commissions are to be formed, one
to handle emergencies such as natural and man-made disasters and
another to map economic reforms.
   Since Gorbachev became Communist Party leader in March 1985, he
has tried to rid Soviet society of a half-century of top-heavy,
bureaucratic management ``by command'' epitomized by dictator Josef
V. Stalin.
   The government ministries were a frequent target during 13 days
of debate in the new Soviet parliament, the Congress of People's
Deputies.
   At one point, deputy Anatoly Miloserdny of Byelorussia blamed the
Council of Ministers for short-sightedness that he said led to ``the
disappearance from sale of the most basic consumer goods.''
   Gorbachev himself urged the deputies to grill the ministers on
why they are dragging their feet on reforms. He acknowledged
complaints that government ministries ``are restructuring very
slowly, if at all'' and said: ``We have to find out what is wrong.''
   Ryzhkov announced nominees for the Cabinet posts today, and the
Supreme Soviet is scheduled to hold confirmation hearings on them
beginning June 19.
   The Congress of People's Deputies wrapped up its session Friday
after hearing Andrei D. Sakharov, 68, father of the Soviet human
rights movement, say the parliament had ``not fulfilled its main
task _ to establish a system of power to overcome economic and
social problems, to put an end to ecological madness.''
   The 1975 Nobel Peace Prize laureate also claimed that by electing
Gorbachev president in an uncontested election and investing him
with far greater powers in his 5-year term, the parliament had given
the Communist Party chief ``absolute personal power.''
   Gorbachev, to loud applause in the Kremlin Palace of Congresses,
vigorously objected to what he termed Sakharov's attempt to
``abase'' the Congress' work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890610-0028 </DOCNO>
