<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0440 06-10 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Train-Bus Collision Kills 31 in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with number of passengers aboard the bus,
Tass' location of accident relative to Moscow, train's speed, background
on previous accident at that site. CORRECTS direction train heading. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train traveling from a Black Sea resort rammed
into a bus in Russia, killing 31 people and injuring at least 14 in
the Soviet Union's second major train accident this week, Tass
reported today.
   The official Soviet news agency said the bus was crossing
railroad tracks at the village of Kamenskaya-Pogorelovo, 640 miles
southwest of Moscow when it was hit by the train Friday afternoon.
   Tass said a railroad worker had flagged the bus driver to move
onto the tracks, but the report did not say if he faced punishment.
   The train, traveling at 50 mph from the popular Black Sea resort
of Adler to the Russian city of Voronezh, could not stop in time to
avoid colliding with the bus, Tass said.
   Twenty-nine people, including two children, were killed instantly
and two died en route to a hospital. Fourteen people were
hospitalized, Tass said.
   The news agency said 46 passengers were on the bus. It did not
say whether the train carried passengers or freight.
   The accident happened at the same spot where 106 people were
killed in a collision of two trains on Aug. 7, 1987, the news agency
reported.
   On Sunday, a gas pipeline exploded as two passenger trains were
passing on the Trans-Siberian Railroad 750 miles southeast of Moscow
in the Ural Mountains. At least 190 passengers were killed and
hundreds injured.
   Last year, 464 Soviets were killed in accidents at railroad
intersections, and 16,013 have died this year in all kinds of
traffic accidents, Tass said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
