<SECOND>PM-Fire Probe, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0434,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frying Pan Blamed for Fire That Left Five Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with police saying frying pan caused
fire, identities of adult victims. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electric pan loaded with grease caught fire and
spread into a blaze that left five people dead and a 2-month-old
child critically injured in an apartment building, police said today.
   Police believe a resident's failure to shut off the frying pan
caused the fire Friday, Sgt. Leonard Sykes said. Earlier, Fire
Department officials said investigators found accelerants on two
stairways, indicating arson.
   Fire officials also found drug paraphernalia and said residents
were ``free-basing,'' or smoking cocaine, in one of the two
second-floor apartments that were destroyed in the three-story
building.
   The free-basing ignited some flames, but it did not appear to
have been the main cause of the fire, Battalion Chief William Foran
said Friday.
   ``You've got five people dead. It's time-consuming to figure out
what happened,'' said Detective Henry Ciolli.
   Police arrested one resident of the building, Renee Riddle, 34,
and charged her with possession of a controlled substance. Several
other people are believed to have escaped from the apartments, the
only ones destroyed in the 24-unit courtyard building.
   Firefighters found the second floor engulfed in flames when they
arrived at the building on the city's South Side Friday afternoon,
said department spokesman Scott La Greca. Rescue efforts were
hampered by security bars on the rear windows of one apartment,
Foran said.
   Dexter Moore, 2 months old, was hospitalized in very critical
condition with smoke inhalation and serious burns. Jesse Whitlow,
31, was listed in serious condition with burns and smoke inhalation.
   Those killed were identified as Laurie Mims, 24, Aretha Hill, 27,
and her three daughters, Melody, 10, Wendy, 2, and Ashley, 11 months
old.
</TEXT>
