<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--MiniskirtBan     06-10 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Miniskirt Ban,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Social Event, Shocked by Antics, Bans Miniskirts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shocked by antics at last year's Berkeley Ball and
threatened with a loss of royal patronage, organizers have banned
miniskirts for next month's charity event.
   And, just to make sure there are no more pictures of disheveled
young women in awkward clinches with drunken swains, only a single,
discreet photorapher selected by Buckingham Palace will be admitted.
   ``Last year's ball was simply awful,'' society hostess Sally
Farmiloe was quoted as saying in Saturday's Daily Mail.
   ``It was full of scrubbers (loose women), second-hand car dealers
and their bimbos. They were wearing leather jackets and tight
miniskirts, not evening wear at all, the sort of clothes you'd wear
to a barbecue.''
   This year's invitations prescribe gowns, ``minimum length below
midcalf.''
   Buckingham Palace let it be known that royal attendance might be
off unless the ball cleaned up its act.
   Organizers said Friday they have been assured that the dancers
will include the Duchess of York, familiarly known as Fergie, who is
patron of the Anastasia Trust for the Deaf. The ball is expected to
raise $160,000 for the charity.
</TEXT>
