<SECOND>AM-BRF--Greece-Clash,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>40 Hurt In Clash Between Socialists and Conservative Youth Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALONICA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of youths preparing for giant
political rallies by Greece's two major political parties clashed in
Salonica on Saturday, and police said at least 40 people were
injured.
   The clashes occurred before dawn as the youths belonging to the
governing Panhellenic Socialist Movement and the conservative New
Democracy Party were putting up posters in this northern city in
preparation for political rallies scheduled for Sunday and Monday
night.
   Both parties are reportedly busing in thousands of supporters in
a show of strength for the crucial June 18 national elections.
   Witnesses said the Socialist Movement youths destroyed two house
trailers and a campaign office used by the New Democrats.
   New Democracy youths reportedly retaliated by smashing the
windows of a Socialist Movement campaign bureau and attacked the
opposing youths with clubs.
   It took riot police two hours to restore calm. Police said at
least 40 people were injured, most slightly, by clubs and stones.
