<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BeerBan     06-10 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Beer Ban,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moi Bans Homemade Beer In Kenya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi on Saturday
banned the brewing and drinking of homemade beer in Kenya, state
radio reported.
   ``I am not prepared to lead a drunken nation,'' the Voice of
Kenya quoted Moi as saying. ``From today, June 10, all brewing and
drinking of traditional beer, even during traditional ceremonies,
must cease.''
   Moi, a church-goer and a teetotaler, made the announcement at a
fund-raising event in Kericho, the headquarters of the tea-growing
region in western Kenya, 160 miles from Nairobi.
   In Kenya, various brands of traditional beer are made at home
from fermented honey, sugar cane, coconut, and grains such as corn,
millet and sorghum. Most people obtained a license from a
low-ranking official before making such beer, but others simply did
so without getting a permit.
   Homemade beer is a favorite drink among Kenyans, particularly in
the countryside, during social occasions such as weddings and
funerals.
   Moi did not mention other alcoholic beverages. Kenya manufactures
whiskey, vodka, gin, liquor, four commercial beers and small
quantities of fruit wines.
</TEXT>
