<FIRST>u w AM-China-WhoKnows?     06-10 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Who Knows?,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush and His Old China Hands Have Few Tea Leaves to Read</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intelligence experts say they're not surprised
that President Bush admits he can't say for sure ``who's calling the
shots'' in China.
   ``Real time intelligence _ that is what is happening now _ is
almost impossible to come by,'' said one administration official.
   The official, who is familiar with the daily intelligence
briefings prepared by the Departments of State and Defense, the CIA
and other sources, said the president's comment that the situation
in China is ``very, very murky'' came directly from such reports.
   At one point, Bush even joked about the problem, saying he'd
called China's 84-ear-old leader Deng Xiaoping, but ``the line was
busy. I couldn't get through.''
   The reason U.S. officials have so little information about who
may or may not be in power at any given time, or who gave specific
orders for the savage attack on the pro-democracy demonstrators, is
quite simple, the experts say.
   ``There's no access. ... If they don't want to respond to the
president of the United States, they sure as hell aren't going to
respond to the ambassador,'' the administration official said.
   He, and others speaking on intelligence matters, spoke only on
condition that their names and exact titles not be used.
   China, which only began to open up during the past decade, has
traditionally posed a problem for foreigners seeking detailed
information.
   The leaders sequester themselves in special compounds and are not
seen unless they wish to be seen. They tend to keep their decisions
within a very tight circle, and for the most part, have had nearly
complete control over the mass media.
   The dearth of human intelligence _ that gleaned by personal
contact _ has been ``a big difficulty'' in the current unrest, the
administration official said.
   U.S. diplomats tend to be exposed to their counterparts who
``spout the party line'' in normal times, said another source
familiar with the diplomatic scene in Beijing.
   ``So when there is a undoubted conflict within the party,
government and top military leadership, they are especially careful
to keep it obscure from the rest of the world,'' said the diplomatic
source.
   During the past week, U.S. Ambassador James Lilley has met twice
with the vice foreign minister in Beijing, and Secretary of State
James A. Baker III has called the Chinese ambassador to the State
Department twice.
   Embassy officials have contacted officials from the Chinese
ministry of national defense, the ministry of education and the
civil aviation administration.
   Also, contacts have taken place with some Chinese military
officers who are personally acquainted with U.S. officials in
Beijing, and they have been providing some information. ``But it's
not very satisfactory,'' the administration official said.
   The official admitted with some frustration that ``we don't have
any feel for what is going on'' in what he called ``the dark
stretches'' of provincial China.
   The diplomatic source said the government has ``ample reports''
about the situation in Beijing. ``But there is an important
distinction between being able to observe what is going on the
outside and having access to the inner workings of the party and
government,'' he said.
   The administration official pointed out that information culled
from technical sources such as satellite photos or electronic
surveillance can only go so far in providing up-to-date information.
   ``Overhead photos ... pictures of troops massed and locations and
tanks, that isn't going to tell you who does what to whom'' during a
group-by-group or person-to-person struggle for political power,
said the official.
   Although he refused to specifically discuss electronic
surveillance, the official noted that the sheer volume of
information poses a problem.
   ``You have a whole mass of information to sort out ... it has to
translated, analyzed, and sometimes only after the fact ... do you
find something has happened,'' he said.
   One important source of information is the news media, and U.S.
officials freely admitted they had their eyes glued to the
round-the-clock coverage provided by the 24-hour Cable News Network.
   ``CNN has been one of the sturdy resources for information''
during the Beijing crackdown, the administration official said.
   ``We cannot presume to do without the information that the media
transmit,'' said another, calling the presence of the U.S.
television networks ``of tremendous importance.''
   The United States also cooperates with other foreign embassies in
China, but ``everybody's been somewhat embarrassed, really, at how
difficult and unsuccessful they've been in getting any
information,'' the administration official said. ``We're all in the
same boat.''
   Sometimes, the official said, expectations are just too high.
   ``It's a magic word _ people really think that `intelligence'
people are omniscient, but boy, they sure aren't,'' the official
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
