<FIRST>r a AM-IvyLeagueTrial     06-10 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ivy League Trial,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvard Student Convicted of Six Armed, Ski-Mask Robberies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A onetime altar boy who escaped the
barrio to become a Harvard University student was convicted of
pulling six armed robberies during college vacations.
   Jose Luis Razo, 22, showed no emotion as he was convicted Friday
by an Orange County Superior Court jury.
   ``I think that none of us wanted to find him guilty,'' said juror
Dean Montanye. ``But there was just too much evidence on most of the
counts. And we couldn't get his excellent memory out of our minds.''
   The prosecution rested heavily on a videotaped confession in
which Razo recounted with vivid detail the holdups by a gunman in a
ski mask. Defense attorney John Barnett maintained it was a false
confession given in a stupor induced by the drug phencyclidine,
better known as PCP or angel dust.
   Jurors, who deliberated three days, acquitted Razo of four other
robbery counts, including two that he had confessed to. But they
also convicted him of trying to escape from police after his arrest
in 1987.
   He faces a maximum sentence of 15 years and four months in
prison. Sentencing is scheduled for Aug. 4.
   Razo was charged with committing 10 armed robberies between
December 1985 and June 1987. In the confession, Razo told detectives
he robbed fast-food restaurants, grocery stores, a dairy and a drug
store.
   Razo testified that he confessed to the robberies in a
drug-driven schizophrenic episode, describing crimes actually
committed by a friend and drug dealer, Richard Longoria.
   When Deputy District Attorney Ravi Mehta pointed out that the
friend was in jail during three of the robberies, Razo's lawyer
suggested those holdups were committed by his client's younger
brother, Albert.
   Razo, a product of a poor La Habra neighborhood was an altar boy
and Boys Club ``Boy of the Year,'' and an ``A'' student at his Roman
Catholic high school. A standout prep football player, he was wooed
by more than 60 colleges when he graduated.
   He chose a scholarship to Harvard, where just 4.7 percent of the
student body is Hispanic. As a freshman in 1985, he decided to major
in psychology.
   ``He always said, `Look how good I'm doing. I'm Mexican. I'm
trying to make it in a white world,''' his sister, Martha, once told
an interviewer.
   But in a jail interview right after his confession and arrest in
July 1987, he said: ``At Harvard, I didn't fit. I'm a homeboy now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
