<FIRST>r a AM-NavyFire     06-10 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Fire,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Fire Found in Navy Vessel; 14 Sailors Suffer Smoke Inhalation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH NAVAL STATION, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen sailors suffered
smoke inhalation when a Navy helicopter carrier caught fire in port,
but there was no serious damage to the ship.
   The Peleliu, an amphibious assault ship used as a helicopter
carrier, caught fire on Friday night, Lt. Cmdr. Steve Chesser said.
   The fire apparently broke out in the circuit breaker room, where
a cable from the shore powers the ship while in port. The cause of
the fire was not known, but an investigation was under way.
   The damage was minimal and the 14 sailors who suffered smoke
inhalation were treated and returned to onboard duty by Saturday
morning, Chesser said.
   The fire was put out by approximately 10:30 p.m., less then 20
minutes after it was discovered, and repairs to the ship will be
made by the crew.
   The Peleliu had recently returned from operations, but Chesser
did not know the nature of the assignment. The ship normally has a
crew of 900.
   Long Beach is located 20 miles southwest of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
