<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Burma-Schools     06-10 0129</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Burma-Schools,0136</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma to Begin Reopening Public Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma, which closed its public schools
during a student-led uprising last year, will begin reopening them
soon.
   The spokesman for Burma's ruling military council, Col. Aung
Thein, told reporters Friday that primary schools will open June 19
``followed by the reopening of middle schools and high schools.''
   He did not say if universities would be allowed to reopen. They
were the focal point of the uprising from March to September in 1988.
   Thousands of protesters were killed in a series of harsh
crackdowns on dissent before the army finally re-established control
on Sept. 18.
   Aung said attendance at the nation's public schools will not be
compulsory. He also warned that student activism will not be
tolerated.
</TEXT>
