<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Lieftinck     06-10 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Lieftinck,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lieftinck, Dutch Public Financier and IMF Official, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pieter Lieftinck, a former Dutch
finance minister and top official of the International Monetary
Fund, died Saturday of heart failure. He was 86.
   Lieftinck died suddenly at his Hague home, said a relative, who
spoke with The Associated Press on condition of anonymity.
   Lieftinck, who was born on Sept. 30, 1902, became a lifelong
member of the Dutch Labor Party.
   He devoted his life to monetary and tax reform and served as a
delegate to the World Bank and the IMF in Washington from 1956 to
1976.
   He was finance minister from 1945-1952 and oversaw the financial
side of the Netherlands' recovery from the destruction of World War
II.
   During his stint as finance minister, Lieftinck implemented
far-reaching monetary reforms, steep tax hikes to finance the
nation's emerging welfare state and the nationalizing of De
Nederlandsche Bank, the Dutch central bank.
   Before the war, Lieftinck was a professor of economics in
Rotterdam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
