<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 1629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Aid     06-10 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Aid,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's 1988 Foreign Aid Totals $9.1 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's aid to Third World nations rose 22.5 percent
to $9.1 billion last year, second only to the United States'
estimated $9.8 billion in grants to developing countries, the
Foreign Ministry said Saturday.
   Development aid as a percentage of Japan's gross national product
was 0.32 percent, up from the previous year's 0.31 percent, the
ministry said in an annual report.
   Of the total, $6.4 billion went directly to developing nations,
the report said. That included $2.9 billion in grants and $3.5
billion in loans.
   Indirect assistance through the United Nations and other
international organizations was $2.7 billion, up 22.9 percent over
1987, the report said.
   The government earmarked $5.4 billion in the 1989 budget in
direct funding, ministry officials said. An additional $5 billion in
development assistance will be provided in loans and investments,
bringing total aid to more than $10 billion. That would make Japan
the world's largest aid donor, officials said.
   Japan has felt foreign pressure in recent years to do more for
developing nations.
</TEXT>
