<FIRST>u p AM-WilderNomination     06-10 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wilder Nomination,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lt. Gov. Wilder Nominated For Virginia Governorship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L. Douglas Wilder, in his quest to become
the first black governor since Reconstruction, was tapped Saturday
as the Democratic nominee at the party convention.
   ``You had the courage to stand with me four years ago,'' Wilder
said, in reference to his 1985 underdog campaign that made him the
first black elected to statewide office in Virginia.
   Also nominated were businessman Donald S. Beyer Jr. for
lieutenant governor and Mary Sue Terry for a second term as attorney
general.
   Under state law, Democratic Gov. Gerald L. Baliles cannot run for
a second consecutive term.
   ``The experts said it couldn't be done,'' said Wilder, a
58-year-old father of three whose daughter Lynn, an artist, gave one
of the seconding speeches for his nomination. ``But together, we did
it.''
   Ms. Wilder said her father taught her to be undaunted by risks.
   A Wilder victory on Nov. 7 would make him the first elected black
governor in U.S. history. At least one black served as governor, but
not as an elected governor, for a time in the South during the
period after the Civil War.
   His Republican opponent will be chosen Tuesday in a bitterly
contested primary from among former U.S. Sen. Paul S. Trible Jr.,
former Attorney General J. Marshall Coleman and U.S. Rep. Stanford
E. Parris.
   Polls released last week showed the three GOP contenders
neck-and-neck and each slightly leading Wilder in a head-to-head
contest. But the Democratic ticket has swept all three offices in
the last two statewide elections, including Wilder's
precedent-setting victory as lieutenant governor four years ago.
   ``The people of Virginia do not want to turn back,'' Wilder said.
``They know Virginia is moving in the right direction. They want to
continue our progress and prosperity.''
   Wilder praised Baliles and his predecessor, former Gov. Charles
S. Robb, even though he has publicly feuded with both men on issues
ranging from tax policy to giving credit for election victories.
   At the convention, the three men clasped hands and raised them as
the 5,300 delegates and alternates cheered.
   Robb, now a U.S. senator, said in a seconding speech for Wilder
that their differences ``pale by comparison to what those
Republicans are saying about each other.'' He said he might not have
been elected lieutenant governor in 1977 and governor in 1981
without Wilder's help.
   Baliles, who was the target of a coal miners' protest at the
convention, said Wilder reminds him of the verse of poetry that
ends, ``Paddle your own canoe.''
   ``Well, I've looked out the window of the governor's office on
more than one occasion and, sure enough, there was Doug paddling by.
But he was always nice about it. He always waved,'' Baliles said.
   He said he admires Wilder because ``he knows what he believes in
and has the courage to stand and be counted.''
   About 150 labor delegates at the convention stood silently and
turned their backs to Baliles while the governor delivered the
keynote speech. The protest was over the sending of state troopers
to the southwest mountains, where some 1,700 members of the United
Mine Workers union have been on strike since April against the
Pittston Coal Group operations.
   ``We think he's turned his back on us by putting at least a third
of the state police out there escorting coal trucks and harassing
our people,'' said Sam Church, a convention delegate from Wise
County and former president of the UMW.
   Wilder, a grandson of slaves and a former state senator from
Richmond, came to the convention unopposed for the nomination. A bid
by state Sen. Daniel W. Bird Jr. of Wythe drew little support and
Bird dropped out of the contest earlier this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
