<FIRST>r a AM-ChineseProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0492 06-10 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slain Chinese Students Honored by White House, Bishop</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The two ceremonies ...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with demonstrations in Washington, New Jersey, edit for transition; picks
up 4th graf, `The two ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bishop of Shanghai, jailed for 30 years by
the Chinese Communists until his May 1988 release, called for
freedom and peace in his homeland during a memorial Mass on Saturday
for the students slain in Beijing.
   Bishop Ignatius Kung, who was released from a Chinese prison for
medical reasons, made his comments shortly after the secretary of
the interior laid a memorial wreath at the Statue of Liberty ``as an
eternal reminder of the cause'' for which the students died.
   In Washington, 500 to 600 people protested outside the Chinese
Embassy, and erected a 20-foot plaster replica of the Statue of
Liberty in a nearby park. The statue, however, was barely visible
from the embassy because it was largely shielded by tall bushes.
   About 200 Chinese students and supporters demonstrated in the
northern New Jersey city of Morristown under banners with such
messages as ``Give Me Freedom Or Give Me Death'' and ``Students In
Beijing, We Stand On Your Side.''
   The two ceremonies in New York marked the second consecutive day
of pro-student activities in the city in the wake of last weekend's
shootings in China. On Friday, more than 15,000 people packed Dag
Hammarskjold Plaza outide the United Nations after a memorial
service and mock funeral procession through Chinatown.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr., saying the spirit of the
pro-democracy forces would never be forgotten, placed the memorial
wreath on Liberty Island at a brief Saturday morning ceremony.
   ``Sadly, we come here today to commemorate those who lost their
lives in the quest for freedom in their own lands,'' said Lujan.
``We were horrified by the brutal reminder that there are strong
forces in this world who seek to snuff out the flame of liberty.''
   Lujan, standing beneath the Statue of Liberty, thanked the
students for inspiring Americans by erecting the Goddess of
Democracy, a statue inspired by Miss Liberty that stood in Tiananmen
Square.
   Later, about 100 people filled the Transfiguration Church in
Chinatown to hear Kung deliver his comments.
   ``I am happy to be here, but at the same time very sad,'' Kung
said in his sermon, which was read by a translator. ``I am happy to
pray for human rights, but sad for the innocent youths who have been
brutally murdered.''
   The 88-year-old bishop was jailed in 1958 for his refusal to
renounce papal authority. Since his release last year, Kung has
since been receiving medical treatment in Stamford, Conn.
   ``The death of the Chinese young students is a great tragedy in
Chinese history. All of you who live in freedom, through your
prayers, must support our suffering brethren,'' said Kung.
   After saying Mass, the frail, bespectacled bishop blessed a
shrine inside the church set up to ``Beijing's Tiananmen Square
martyrs.'' A dozen wreaths sent by various groups in Chinatown
surrounded the shrine.
   After the Mass, dozens of parishioners lined up to pray at the
memorial. In the schoolyard adjoining the church, pro-student groups
set up tables to collect donations in the fight for democracy.
   There was one pocket of support for the Chinese government's
decision to use military force against the students. Sara Flounders,
a member of the national committee of the Workers World Party, said
the socialist organization backed the Chinese government.
   ``We feel it's in the interest of the working people and
oppressed people all over the world to support the Chinese
government,'' she said, labeling the student uprising ``a
counter-revolutionary development.''
</TEXT>
