<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 1638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RockyFlats     06-10 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocky Flats Presents One Image Externally; Has Another Internally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two faces of the Rocky Flats nuclear plant were
presented by its operators and its federal overseers, an affidavit
and internal memos revealed after federal raids shut down the
facility as unsafe last week.
   Hazardous wastes were burned illegally in a plutonium
reprocessing building while it was closed for safety violations, the
affidavit states, yet the Department of Energy paid Rocky Flats'
managers bonuses each year as rewards for production and management.
   A July 1986 Energy Department internal memorandum said Rocky
Flats was ``in poor condition generally in terms of environmental
compliance'' and its permit applications were ``grossly deficient.''
The memo also indicated some of the plant's waste facilities were
``patently illegal.'' Plutonium triggers are made at the plant,
northwest of Denver.
   Yet an ad for Rockwell International, the facility's operator,
appears in the current edition of a metropolitan weekly, the
Broomfield Enterprise, inviting the public to tour the plant.
Officials said the tours were the company's method of explaining to
neighboring communities how the nuclear weapons plant operated and
why.
   The Rocky Mountain News quoted an unidentified Rockwell spokesman
as saying that the ad was placed before the investigation.
   Another DOE memo, written July 14, 1986, said favorable news
media attention had been garnered for Rocky Flats officials who
negotiated a cleanup agreement with regulators, rather than the bad
press they might have deserved.
   ``Much of the good press we have gotten from the agreement ...
has taken attention away from just how really bad this site is,''
the memo said.
   Energy Department officials supported the statements of Rockwell
executives about plant safety and performance they allegedly knew
were false, according to the affidavit that was unsealed Friday in
U.S. District Court here.
   The affidavit was made public after it had been used earlier in
the week by federal agents to obtain warrants for the raids.
   Some of Rocky Flats' top managers since 1980 are among the DOE
and Rockwell officials named in the affidavit as possible
co-conspirators in violation of hazardous waste laws.
   They include Energy Department officials Earl Whiteman and
Raymond Romatowski, as well as Rockwell executives Dominic Sanchini
and J.E. Door. But representatives of the department and Rockwell
declined to comment on the affidavit.
   It says DOE and Rockwell officials are suspected of collaborating
on making low waste estimates at Rocky Flats. They also are accused
of making false statements regarding waste disposal at the facility.
   At that time, the plant's plutonium-reprocessing facility,
Building 771, was supposed to be shut down for four months afer
three safety inspectors were accidentally exposed to radiation.
   But the FBI, using infrared cameras during flights over Rocky
Flats in December, detected burning in an incinerator in Building
771.
   Meanwhile, Whiteman and Sanchini publicly were saying the
building totally was shut down.
   Whiteman and Dorr also were accused of misleading regulators in
1985 by certifying that Rocky Flats' groundwater monitoring system
complied with federal requirements. The affidavit says that
certification was found to be false and in violation of federal law.
   Whiteman and other Energy Department officials were accused of
claiming that a number of wastes were nonhazardous, when in fact
they were hazardous.
   A Nov. 13, 1987, Energy Department memo by Romatowski to other
department officials advised that the agency should resist the
efforts of environmental and public health authorities trying to
clean up Rocky Flats.
   The General Accounting Office also is conducting an investigation
into performance bonuses awarded Rocky Flats' managers.
   The DOE paid bonuses each year, ranging from $2.3 million in 1981
to $9.4 million last year, to reward Rockwell for its production and
management performance at Rocky Flats.
   In addition to the raid by FBI and EPA agents, the plant also
came under fire Wednesday from the Colorado Department of Health,
which announced it had found 25 environmental and procedural
violations at the plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
