<DOCNO> AP890610-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 1641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-10 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Duel Kills 4, Amid Arab Mediation Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners exchanged
rocket and artillery fire Saturday, killing four people and wounding
12.
   Arab officials, meanwhile, sought to halt the fighting and
reportedly were trying to gain support for a peace plan to end
Lebanon's 14-year civil war.
   A police spokesman said the Syrians, entrenched in Moslem west
Beirut, blasted the Christian coastline north of Beirut with 130mm
howitzer shells and 107mm rockets.
   One round struck a residential district near the port of Jounieh,
12 miles north of Beirut, killing four people and wounding seven, he
said on condition of anonymity.
   Five other civilians were wounded in a retaliatory barrage on
west Beirut during which Christian units under Gen. Michel Aoun
opened up with 155mm howitzers, he said.
   The latest casualties brought the overall toll to 367 people
killed and 1,432 wounded since the latest round of fighting began on
March 8 between Aoun's 20,000 forces and allied Syrian and Druse
Moslem fighters.
   The clash began when Aoun's forces blockaded illegal ports run by
Moslem militias that Aoun said cost the state treasury about $100
million yearly. Syria responded by blockading the 310-square-mile
Christian enclave.
   Thuds of exploding shells shook the capital as Lakhdar Ibrahimi,
an Arab League envoy, shuttled twice between the Christian and
Moslem sectors for talks with Aoun, who heads the Christian Cabinet
in Lebanon's dual government, and Salim Hoss, his Moslem rival.
   The Arab League called a cease-fire on May 11 but the fighting
did not stop. The league renewed the call at a summit meeting in
Casablanca, Morocco, May 23-26 and appointed a three-member
committee to devise a peace plan.
   But Syrian forces kept shelling the Christian coastline, claiming
they wanted to prevent Iraqi supplies from reaching Aoun by sea.
These barrages have drawn occasional retaliation from Aoun's forces.
   Ibrahimi, an Algerian diplomat, left for Syria later Saturday.
   The Arab committee is comprised of Morocco's King Hassan II, King
Fahd of Saudi Arabia and President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria.
   Their foreign ministers arrived in Baghdad, Iraq, Saturday after
three days of talks in Damascus with Syrian President Hafez Assad
and Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, who reportedly pledged to
assist their mission.
   Syria and Iraq, the Arab world's traditional rivals, are on
opposite sides of the Lebanese civil war.
   Syria, with 40,000 troops in northern and eastern provinces as
well as west Beirut, is the Moslems' main supporter. Iraq supports
Aoun, who has vowed to drive the Syrians out of Lebanon.
   The independent Beirut daily An-Nahar said the Arab foreign
ministers were soliciting support for a seven-point settlement
proposal.
   The plan, according to the paper, calls for ``exerting
international pressure on Israel to withdraw its forces from south
Lebanon.'' Israel has occupied a self-designated ``security sone''
in south Lebanon since 1985 in an effort to stop cross-border
guerrilla raids.
   According to An-Nahar, the peace proposal would include the
``deployment of an Algerian force'' along a 75-mile-long coastal
stretch from Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut, to Tripoli, to prevent
the import and export of illegal goods.
   It also calls for lifting all sea, land and air blockades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
