<DOCNO> AP890610-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 1702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Shanghai     06-10 0903</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Shanghai,0937</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arrests, Government Warnings Keep China's Largest City Under Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANGHAI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of bicycles clog cratered
streets, electric trolleys lumber down tree-shaded avenues and dim
neon signs flicker above hole-in-the-wall bars.
   Shanghai grinds on after authorities made some arrests and issued
warnings of tougher action aimed at preventing China's largest city
from becoming the new focal point for the pro-democracy movement
crushed in Beijing last week.
   The fist of authority has come down, less forcefully in Shanghai
than elsewhere, but strong enough to stifle the reappearing
protests. Security forces have swept through Chinese cities in
recent days arresting scores of students and workers, including at
least 21 in Shanghai.
   In the last few days protesters wrought havoc on Shanghai's
traffic, blocking intersections with buses and concrete barricades.
   On Friday they held a rally in People's Square that drew 50,000
supporters _largest anywhere in China since the bloody suppression
of the democracy uprising June 3-4 that left at least 3,000 dead.
   Facing virtually no opposition from authorities in Shanghai,
which unlike Beijing is not under martial law, activists seemed
headed toward shifting the focus of the fight for freedom and
expanded rights to this city of 12 million.
   Shanghai Mayor Zhu Rongji gave what was viewed as a conciliatory
speech Thursday, urging civic obedience so troops would not be
called into the city.
   But authorities issued a clear warning against further unrest.
   ``We want to sternly warn certain ... students not to go any
further on this dangerous road,'' Shanghai radio said Saturday.
``There is a limit to the restraint of the people of Shanghai.''
   There was also a heavy police presence Saturday, with a motorcade
of 17 police motorcycles with sidecars and a small convoy of trucks
carrying workers urging rigid support of the Communist Party
swooping through the city.
   A major handicap for students' propaganda efforts is the lack of
news about what has happened in the capital 670 miles to the
northwest.
   ``The government says 23 students were killed, but how do we know
way down here in Shanghai?'' asked a 33-year-old delivery man.
   ``We know the students say many more were killed than the
government says, but we have no idea who's right,'' a mechanic said.
``We don't get any news.''
   Since before last week's bloody crackdown in Beijing, provincial
students had been returning to the countryside to inform the masses
about the revolution.
   But Shanghai students have not been particularly energetic in
spreading the word.
   There were scattered posters in Shanghai earlier this week
calling for a general strike, but they have largely disappeared,
residents say.
   Instead, Shanghai citizens seem to be absorbed in other kinds of
posters. In the city center, people stared intently at pictures of a
bodybuilding contest, movie promotions and shoe advertisements
tacked up along raucous Nanjing Road.
   Several clusters of people gathered at People's Square Saturday
to exchange opinions about the previous day's mass rally.
   ``I'm outraged, but I'm very afraid. I don't dare speak out,'' a
research scientist said. ``Our media is just communist party
propaganda. We all listen to the Voice of America and BBC broadcasts
every day to hear the truth.'' Several people around him nodded.
   Like all those interviewed in Shanghai, the scientist insisted
that his name not be used. The Chinese government began a new form
of terror Saturday, playing foreign news reports on television and
urging informers to identify Chinese who spoke on camera.
   About 200 students from Shahghai's Fudan and Tongji universities
held a rally and sit-in in front of Shanghai police headquarters to
demand the release of nine labor leaders arrested Friday.
   ``If they decided to press charges then they must do so in the
open, but they insist on doing it secretly,'' said a student leader
from Tongji University at the protest.
   The arrests appeared to be part of a nationwide campaign to
create a split between students and workers. By cracking down on
labor, authorities undermine a main source of support for the
student movement.
   At Fudan University, about 90 percent of the students have
returned to their homes out of fear of troops entering campus to
arrest students.
   Along the main path into campus there is an 8-foot plastic foam
model of the statue of liberty made by a neighboring school and
paraded around the city in marches before the May 20 imposition of
martial law in Beijing.
   Student leaders were divided earlier this week over whether to
continue disrupting city life.
   ``We finally agreed to an end to the barricades because the loss
in production caused by them becomes the people's burden,'' one
senior said.
   Diplomatic sources estimated production fell off in Shanghai, a
major industrial base, by as much as 50 percent after the barricades
caused widespread absenteeism at factories.
   With arrests stepping up in the last few days, it is time for the
democracy movement to pause and assess its lessons, students
interviewed at Fudan said.
   ``Most peasants don't understand our 1989 movement at all,'' one
freshman said. ``We must now concentrate on bringing the peasants
into play.
   Sheer fear and a need for quiet reflection are thus likely to
keep Shanghai from becoming the kind of rallying point for democracy
that Beijing was.
   ``The people of Shanghai are not cowards,'' said a young bank
teller at People's Square. ``But we are afraid of getting killed.''
</TEXT>
