<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     06-10 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Child Killed, 29 Arabs Wounded in Clashes with Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers opened fire Saturday on
Palestinians protesting new identity cards and an 8-year-old boy was
struck in the chest and fatally wounded, a doctor reported.
   Hospital officials said the boy was one of 30 Arabs wounded
during clashes with troops in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   According to residents of the Jabaliya refugee camp in the Gaza
Strip, soldiers in jeeps used loudspeakers to announce that a
week-long military curfew on the strip would be lifted to allow
residents to obtain new computerized identity cards. The cards are
needed for Palestinians to work in Israel.
   Khader Muranakh, a camp resident, said about 200 Palestinians
began a protest march shouting slogans against the new cards.
   ``Youths started pelting the troops with stones and the soldiers
then opened fired,'' said United Nations nurse Muhammad Hamudeh.
   A doctor at the U.N. Relief and Works Administration clinic in
the camp said Shadi Ziad Rabah Awad, 8, was hit in the chest by a
rubbet-coated metal pellet and died despite an emergency operation.
   Muranakh said the boy was standing outside his uncle's home
watching the demonstration when troops opened fire from about two
yards away and wounded him.
   An army spokesman confirmed the death, but gave the boy's age as
12. The spokesman did not provide the circumstances of the death.
   Army officials have accused Palestinian activists of encouraging
children to participate in protests to act as shields for older
organizers and to serve propaganda purposes when they are wounded.
   Awad's death raised to 514 the number of Palestinians killed
since the uprising began 18 months ago. Twenty-two Israelis also
have been slain in the violence.
   Arab reports said 28 Palestinians, including Awad, were wounded
in the Gaza Strip. They said two Palestinians were wounded in
clashes in the West Bank town of Ramallah.
   The army announced late Saturday that the curfew would remain in
effect on the Jabaliya refugee camp when it is lifted from the rest
of the Gaza Strip on Sunday.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said in a radio interview that the
army had succeeded in breaking a boycott ordered by the underground
leadership of the uprising.
   The leadership called on the 1.7 million Palestinians in the
occupied lands to stop paying taxes, tear up identity cards, and not
cooperate with the military government.
   ``The opposite has happened,'' Rabin said. ``The individual today
needs and depends on the civil administration, and therefore there
is no more talk of a popular revolt.''
   ``On the other hand, we have not been able to prevail over the
sporadic stone throwings,'' he said.
</TEXT>
