<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-POWs     06-10 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-POWs,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. To Interview Monk Who Reportedly Saw American POWs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is sending a military attache to
interview a Japanese monk who reportedly saw American POWs in
Vietnamese prison camps recently, despite Hanoi's assertions that it
holds no prisoners.
   The Buddhist monk, Iwanobu Yoshida, 65, has been hospitalized in
northern Japan with what are termed mental and physical problems
since he was freed in January after 14 years' imprisonment in
Vietnam.
   In the past week, Japanese media reports and his daughter have
said that Yoshida shared a cell with Americans in the re-education
camp where he was held.
   The Vietnamese Embassy in Tokyo denied the claims, reiterating
that Hanoi holds no prisoners from the war, which ended in 1975.
   But the U.S. government has for years pressed Hanoi for an
accounting of the 1,730 Americans listed as missing in action in
Vietnam and 634 missing elsewhere in the war zone.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said Saturday that a military attache
planned to fly to northern Sapporo Sunday to interview Yoshida and
the information will be relayed to Washington for analysis.
   The United States sought to interview Yoshida earlier but until
now had been turned down by his daughter, Keiko Takatsuka, on
grounds he was too ill, said the embassy spokesman on condition of
anonymity.
   Ms. Takatsuka on Saturday said her father had shared a cell with
three American prisoners for the last six years before returning to
Japan.
   ``My father told me that when he asked them if they were
Americans, they nodded,'' Ms. Takatsuka said in an interview from
her home in Sapporo on Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost island. The
prisoners were not allowed to speak to each other, she said.
   A spokesman for the hospital where Yoshida is being treated said
he suffers from mental disorders and a speech impediment, and only
his daughter can understand what he says.
   Hidenori Hareyama, a spokesman for Shiraishi Tokushukai Hospital
on Hokkaido said that Yoshida's speech is at times incoherent. Ms.
Takutsaka said her father had a stroke three years ago.
   Yoshida had been a city councilman in Mibari on Hokkaido before
he became a monk in 1966 and emigrated to Vietnam. He set up a
temple in Saigon, now Ho Chi Minh City, and became a South
Vietnamese citizen in 1973.
   He was arrested in 1975, after the takeover of South Vietnam by
Communist forces. On Jan. 20, Vietnam released him on humanitarian
grounds after appeals from international human rights groups
including Amnesty International.
   Ms. Takatsuka said her father does not remember the names of the
three held in his cell, but said they were still ``young and
healthy.''
   Yoshida told her he saw more American POWs, perhaps more than 10,
before he suffered a stroke.
   ``My father is still afraid somebody will come and get him to
throw him back in the Vietnamese prison,'' she said.
</TEXT>
