<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Crash     06-10 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crash,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports 31 Killed in Bus-Train Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train crashed into a bus in a village southwest
of Moscow and 31 people were killed in the second major railway
accident in the Soviet Union in less than a week, the official news
agency Tass reported Saturday.
   Tass said the accident occurred Friday afternoon after a railroad
worker flagged the bus driver to go ahead and cross the tracks. The
vehicle was struck by the train traveling 50 mph.
   Tass said at least 14 people were injured in the accident in
Kamenskaya-Pogorelovo, 640 miles southwest of Moscow.
   The train had left the Black Sea resort of Adler and was en route
to Voronezh, according to Tass.
   It reported the bus was carrying 46 passengers but it did not say
if the train was a freight or passenger train and if all of the
casualties were from the bus or if some were aboard the train.
   The agency said the accident happened at the same crossing where
106 people were killed in a collision of two trains on Aug. 7, 1987.
   Last Sunday gas from a pipeline exploded as two passenger trains
were passing on the Trans-Siberian Railroad 750 miles southeast of
Moscow in the Ural Mountains. At least 190 passengers were killed
and hundreds injured.
   Tass said 464 people were killed in accidents at Soviet railroad
crossings last year.
