<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--ContractFraud     06-10 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Contract Fraud,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman Sentenced for Overcharging Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman convicted of overcharging the
government for work at an Army training base has been sentenced to
eight months in prison and a $14,000 fine.
   U.S. District Judge Edward L. Filippine also sentenced Arthur
Kennedy to three years' probation Friday and ordered him to pay the
Defense Department $13,349 in restitution. Kennedy's company, Nimrod
Inc., was fined $6,400.
   Kennedy, president of Nimrod, and his company were convicted
March 17 of overcharging the government by about $13,000 in 1986 and
1987 on a contract to service residential furnaces at Fort Leonard
Wood, a major training base 125 miles southwest of St. Louis.
   A previous trial ended in a mistrial Feb. 6 when jurors said they
couldn't reach a verdict.
   A federal complaint filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court in
Springfield accused the 45-year-old St. Louis man of trying to
regain business at the fort through a third party. Nimrod was
suspended from receiving Army contracts.
