<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Spaggiari     06-10 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Spaggiari,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>France's Most Famous Bank Burglar Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HYERES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Spaggiari, mastermind of the
spectacular ``sewer gang'' bank heist and on the run for 12 years,
died and his body was left outside his mother's house by friends on
Saturday, police and the thief's lawyer reported.
   Police said Spaggiari's body was brought to his mother's home in
this Riviera city early Saturday by two men who fled. Police
specialists confirmed the body was that of Spaggiari, 57, who
underwent plastic surgery after France's most famous bank job in
1976.
   Jacques Peyrat, Spaggiari's lawyer, said his client died of lung
cancer on Friday.
   Spaggiari, who had a photography business in Nice, formed the
gang of ``sewer rats'' who tunneled their way into the Societe
Generale bank in Nice and over a weekend, July 17-19, 1976, opened
337 safe deposit boxes. They made off with gold, jewelry and
negotiable paper worth an estimated $6,835,812.
   The gang paddled a mile down a sewer and dug a tunnel 25 feet
long from the sewer to the back of the bank.
   Spaggiari was arrested shortly after the break-in but escaped
March 10, 1977.
   Two books, including Spaggiari's own account, were written on the
exploit and a film was made called ``The Sewers of Paradise.''
</TEXT>
