<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 1907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-LaborMemorial     06-10 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Labor Memorial,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Martyr Joe Hill's Ashes Scattered at Slain Miners' Monument</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS M. SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last ashes of union martyr Joe Hill
were scattered Saturday at a cemetery where five unionized miners
had lain in unmarked graves since being gunned down at a coal mine
nearly 62 years ago.
   ``It's high time you got back among your own people again,'' said
Carlos Cortes, a poet with the Industrial Workers of the World union
in Chicago, as he scattered Hill's ashes over the graves.
   Hill was an organizer for the IWW, one of the earliest unions
whose members were also called Wobblies.
   A granite marker with the names of the slain miners and of a
sixth miner who lies in a family plot in Louisville, Colo., was
unveiled in the green, neatly mowed cemetery about 20 miles
northwest of Denver.
   The dead, who were among 500 striking miners accompanied by wives
and children, were killed at the Columbine Mine on Nov. 21, 1927, by
state militiamen and mine guards using machine guns and rifles. The
strike was organized by the IWW.
   A marker commemorating the Columbine Massacre was unveiled
Saturday on Colorado Highway 7 about a mile south of the old
abandoned mine and four miles east of the cemetery.
   Hill was an immigrant from Sweden who became a Wobbly organizer
and songwriter.
   In 1915, he was executed by a Utah firing squad for the murder of
a grocer in Salt Lake City, where Hill had been organizing workers.
Supporters said the mining industry framed Hill, who maintained his
innocence to the end.
   At his last request, his body was cremated after a Chicago
funeral, and on May Day of 1916 his ashes were divided and scattered
in many states _ except Utah, where he said he wouldn't be caught
dead.
   The envelope containing the ashes scattered Saturday wound up at
the National Archives in Washington through a postal error, and
remained there another seven decades. Last fall, the archives
returned them to the IWW.
   Hill is best known to many modern Americans through the ballad
``Joe Hill,'' which folk singer Joan Baez sang at the Woodstock
Festival in 1969. One stanza runs: ``From San Diego up to Maine@ In
every mine and mill@ Where working men defend their rights@ It's
there you'll find Joe Hill...''
   During a general strike in 1927, the Columbine Mine was the only
one operating. Strikers and some family members went there Nov. 21
to try to persuade miners to join them.
   Rocks were hurled back and forth before a miner climbed up on a
closed gate and yelled, ``Come on!'' He was hauled down by police
and beaten.
   Pickets surged forward and burst through the gate, but were met
by withering gunfire from militiamen and guards, who had at least
two machine guns, according to historians and witnesses.
   Five of the dead _ John Eastenes, 34, of Lafayette; Nick
Spanudakhis, 34, of Lafayette; Frank Kovich of Erie; Jerry Davis,
21, of Frederick; Mike Vidovich, 35, of Erie _ were buried in a plot
at the Lafayette cemetery bought by the Wobblies.
   The Wobblies, however, didn't buy headstones and the miners'
families couldn't afford them.
   The sixth miner killed, Rene Jacques, 26, of Louisville was
buried in his hometown.
   Saturday's ceremonies were sponsored by the IWW, the United Mine
Workers of America, the Colorado Labor Forum and the Erie, Lafayette
and state historical societies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890610-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 1908EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-China     06-10 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-China,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong and Macao Residents Fear Future with China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's bloody crackdown on students demanding
more democracy has sent shivers of fear through Hong Kong and Macao
_ British and Portuguese territories to be turned over to China by
the end of this century.
   Lydia Dunn, a member of Hong Kong's Executive Council (cabinet),
said Saturday that Britain's decision to let only certain categories
of Hong Kong residents resettle in Britain would divide the colony.
   She said Britain has a moral obligation to give a ``home of last
resort'' to all of Hong Kong's 3.25 million people who are entitled
to British passports. A vast majority of Hong Kong's people are
Chinese.
   The colony is to be returned to China in July 1997 under an
agreement signed in 1984.
   In Lisbon, President Mario Soares said Portugal will stand by an
accord signed with China on Macao, a Portugese enclave in southern
China near Hong Kong.
   Under a 1986 agreement Portugal will cede Macao, which has a
population of about 500,000, to China by Dec. 20, 1999.
   In both the British and Portuguese accords China promises to
allow the two territories to maintain democratic structures and
mixed capitalist-socialist economies for at least 50 years after the
transfer of sovereignty.
   Soares expressed concern over the military supression of
pro-democracy groups in China in which hundreds of people were
killed, the Portugese news agency Lusa reported.
   It said in a statement to the people of Macao Soares said a
climate of liberty, democracy and tolerance is needed for economic
progress and social justice.
   Thousands of people in Hong Kong and Macao have joined
demonstrations protesting the violence in China.
   In talks last week between Hong Kong Governor David Wilson and
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher Mrs. Thatcher rejected
proposals to give the right of resettlement to all Hong Kong
residents.
   London newspapers reported Mrs. Thatcher's government was
prepared to admit up to 250,000 Hong Kong residents _ mainly current
and retired civil servants and leading businessmen.
   Hong Kong's lawmaking Legislative Council declared after a
meeting Friday that Britain has ``a fundamental moral duty'' to give
all residents entitled to British passports the right to resettle in
Britain.
   Mrs. Dunn said of the category system: ``We believe it would be a
disservice ... at this time when there is such unity to separate the
community into the haves and the have-nots.''
   She said Britain ``may decide to give out ... `X' number of
passports on some kind of categorization system but the rest will
continue to demand their rights.''
   London's Guardian newspaper reported Hong Kong is prepared to
offer asylum to political refugees from China.
   It quoted Geoffrey Barnes, Hong Kong's secretary for security, as
saying screening procedures have been established at at the border
with China's Guandong province ``even though it is recognized that
this move will add to the growing tensions between Hong Kong and
Beijing.''
   Barnes was in London for talks British officials.
   The Guardian said Barnes stressed that so far there have been no
requests for asylum among the handful of Chinese who cross illegally
into Hong Kong daily. The newspaper said that in the past such
illegal immigrants were sent back to China within 24 hours.
   Anti-China demonstrations were reported Saturday in Portugal and
in Rome.
   Portuguese newspapers said hundreds of university students held
protest rallies and student leaders at Coimbra university declared a
period of mourning until June 14 for the people killed in China's
martial-law crackdown.
   In Rome student representatives delivered to the Chinese Embassy
a petition they said was signed by 12,000 people condemning the
massacre of pro-democracy desmonstrators in Bejing.
   They said the petition also denounced the ``witchhunt'' under way
to seize the leaders of the Beijing demonstrations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
