<FIRST>r a AM-BelmontStakes-Newspage     06-10 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belmont Stakes-Newspage,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Easy Goer Wins The Belmont, Stymies Sunday Silence's Triple Crown
Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Easy Goer, the beaten favorite in the Kentucky
Derby and Preakness, foiled Sunday Silence's bid for the Triple
Crown on Saturday with an eight-length victory in the Belmont Stakes.
   Ridden by Pat Day, the colt's winning time of 2:26 was the second
fastest Belmont in 121 races, after Secretariat's 2:24 when he won
the Triple Crown in 1973 with a 31-length victory.
   Instead of Sunday Silence, the 4-5 favorite, becoming the 12th
winner of the Triple Crown and the first since 1978, he became the
12th 3-year-old to win the Kentucky Derby and Preakness only to lose
the 1{-mile Belmont.
   Sunday Silence, under Pat Valenzuela, was second behind
pace-setter Le Voyageur into the backstretch and Easy Goer was
third. Sunday Silence took the lead midway through the turn, but
Easy Goer snatched it away with a quarter-mile remaining.
   Sunday Silence finished a length ahead of Le Voyageur. Awe
Inspiring was 12 lengths back in fourth, followed by Hawkster, Rock
Point, Imbibe, Irish Actor, Triple Buck and Fire Maker.
   The winner paid $5.20, $2.80 and $2.40 to his backers in an
estimated crowd of more than 60,000. Sunday Silence returned $3 and
$2.60 and Le Voyageur was $4.60 to show.
   The Triple Crown drought is now at least 12 years, second longest
in the history of the series after the 25 years between Citation's
victory in 1948 and Secretariat's in 1973.
</TEXT>
