<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS first item to RECAST lead, moving suicide information to
4th graf, `Vonnegut did...'; SUBS second item to UPDATE throughout with
second store owner agreeing to Gregory's demands; SUBS 4th item to restore
full dateline, VANCOUVER, British Columbia, reflecting pvs sub sent as
a0495. ^LaserPhoto NY44, ROM2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Kurt Vonnegut Jr. came to Ernest
Hemingway country and criticized the legendary writer for being out
of touch with America.
   ``He was in exile ... and he never explained the reason for his
exile, but he hardly knew us,'' Vonnegut said Friday at Boise State
University's ``Hemingway In Idaho'' conference.
   ``I wouldn't think Ketchum would be a place to learn a whole lot
about, you know, American black people, American Hispanics,''
Vonnegut said. Hemingway, who was born in Illinois but spent much of
his life abroad, had a home in Ketchum near the Sun Valley ski
resort in the last years of his life.
   Vonnegut did say that Hemingway, who committed suicide in Idaho
in 1961, was a top-rate artist with ``a soul the size of
Kilimanjaro.''
   Hemingway, who won the Nobel Prize for literature in 1954, wrote
``The Snows of Kilimanjaro,'' ``The Sun Also Rises'' and ``The Old
Man and the Sea.''
   Vonnegut said Hemingway may have seen his suicide as a
punctuation mark, a period, a way of ending the story of his own
life. But, Vonnegut said, life is not a story. A story is something
made up, something closer to a ballet.
   ``Only stories are supposed to be stories,'' said Vonnegut,
author of ``Slaughterhouse Five'' and ``Cat's Cradle.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dick Gregory won a second round Saturday
in his battle to get shops to stop selling glass pipes and other
items that the activist says can be used for drugs.
   Joe Hutson, who had threatened Friday to sue Gregory and others
demonstrating at his store, the Fun Shop, said he gave in because
their protracted protests were bad for business.
   Gregory and several other people had been arrested five times in
the previous two days for refusing to leave Hutson's store, which
sells costume and party supplies as well as the items to which
Gregory objected.
   On Friday, Jim Willis, owner of another store targeted by
Gregory, Pipes Unique, agreed to remove the items and to allow
Gregory to post a sign stating, ``This store sells no merchandise to
be used for any illegal purpose.''
   Gregory was happy with Willis' action but said ``we're really
kind of surprised it took so long.''
   A court hearing on the arrests is scheduled June 22.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Morris, the bad boy of modern dance, returned
to the place that backed him long before he went to Belgium to cause
an international stir with iconoclastic ballets.
   Morris' new work, ``Dido and Aeneas,'' a ballet in which Morris
plays two female parts, received critical acclaim here last week.
   When ``Dido'' had its Brussels premier in March, one reviewer
asked how long that city would have to endure Morris'
``loathsomeness.'' Morris' dance company has two years left on a
three-year residence at the Theatre Royal de la Monnaie.
   Morris, a 32-year-old Seattle, Wash., native who wears his tight
curly hair in long tendrils, says he views this disgruntlement by
the Belgians as xenophobia and discomfort with his acknowledged
homosexuality.
   ``Probably some people have a problem that I play female roles.
They forget about Greek theater and Japanese theater,'' Morris said
of ``Dido'' last week.
   At least Europeans are open to modern dance, which can't be said
of Americans, he said.
   In this country, ``there's not the same sort of governmental and
popular support. In the states, art ... is highfalutin, and that's
unfortunate, because it's not.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gene Hackman won't be packing
a gun in his next film. And he couldn't be happier.
   ``It's a chance for me not to shoot anyone,'' said Hackman, who
is in town for ``Narrow Margin,'' which starts production in British
Columbia this week.
   The 58-year-old actor said Friday that he wants to move away from
shoot-'em-up movies such as the 1971 film ``The French Connection,''
for which he won an Oscar.
   ``I'd be hypocritical if I said I don't believe in violence or do
those kind of films, because I have in the past. I would like in my
later years now to not do so much of that kind of thing and maybe
films that have a little more social comment or more theatrics in
them.''
   Anne Archer, who received an Academy award nomination last year
for her performance in ``Fatal Attraction,'' is Hackman's co-star.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Filming the 1985 Achille Lauro hijacking story aboard
the cruise ship itself had its emotional moments, says Eva Marie
Saint, who plays the wife of the crippled American killed by
terrorists.
   The cast of the television film went aboard the Italian liner
during a regular cruise this spring. At one point, one of the
waiters who lived through the hijacking began crying, the actress
told reporters visiting the film's on-land set at Cinecitta studios
last week.
   ``Many of the waiters had been there during the hijacking ... and
while we were shooting, they lost control and relived the
experience,'' she said.
   Burt Lancaster plays Leon Klinghoffer, the wheelchair-bound New
Yorker who was dumped into the Mediterranean by Palestine
terrorists. Klinghoffer was the only passenger killed in the
hijacking, which ended with the terrorists' surrender to Italian
authorities.
   The film won't be ready for broadcast before 1990.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Washington Redskins owner Jack Kent
Cooke has conceded he is the father of a 16-month-old girl named
Jacqueline Kent Cooke and says he will provide financial support for
the child.
   Referring to the child as ``it,'' a lawyer for Cooke, 76,
acknowledged Cooke's parenthood at a hearing in Fauquier County,
Va., Circuit Court, confirming statements by his ex-wife, Suzanne
Martin Cooke.
   ``We concede that it is our child,'' attorney Milton S. Gould
said, according to a transcript of the April 5 hearing reported
Friday by The Washington Post. ``We have to support it, and we will
support it in such a manner as your honor determines that it is
entitled to.''
   Ms. Cooke, 33, has been fighting for child support from the
sports magnate since he filed for divorce in October 1987, less than
three months after their wedding. Ms. Cooke has alleged that Cooke
was angry that she violated a prenuptial agreement by becoming
pregnant shortly before their marriage.
</TEXT>
