<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Jaruzelski 1stLd-Writethru a0505 06-10 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Jaruzelski, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0505,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Promises Economic Aid To Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead, inserts additional Jaruzelski quotes and changes
to conform throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, still
smarting from his Communist Party's stunning electoral defeat,
received promises Saturday of economic assistance from Britain.
   He was greeted at the start of his two-day visit by
pro-Solidarity demonsrators who demanded he resign.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, after a 3{-hour meeting with
Jaruzelski, promised economic aid to encourage progress ``on the
path of democracy and reform,'' according to a statement issued by
Mrs. Thatcher's office. It said the measures include a $7.75 million
annual contribution to a managerial fund to train Poles in ``a more
market-oriented economy.''
   British sources said the promised help fell short of Jaruzelski's
hopes for new direct credit lines.
   Supporters of Solidarity, the free union movement that won scores
of victories in Sunday's election, demonstrated outside the Polish
Embassy and draped a statue with banners in Solidarity's red and
white colors.
   Jaruzelski commented on the election in an interview with
Britain's Channel 4 television network.
   ``We went into the election as a very fragmented front, in
contrast to Solidarity,'' he said.
   ``Perhaps because we are burdened by a kind of complex of guilt
for so far not having sufficiently applied all sorts of democratic
procedures, we wanted to be super-democratic, super-pluralist,'' he
added.
   Jaruzelski, speaking Polish with his remarks translated into
English, also said ``the reforms are irreversible and we're going to
carry on with them.''
   The statement from Mrs. Thatcher's office said she told
Jaruzelski she welcomed the communist authorities' promise to stand
by the election results.
   Mrs. Thatcher also said Britain will play a role in getting
Poland's $38 billion foreign debt rescheduled by Western creditors,
according to the statement released after the meeting. But it said
Britain will encourage new loans only under an International
Monetary Fund economic reform program.
   Outside the Polish Embassy, Tadek Jarski, leader of the
British-based movement Solidarity with Solidarity, said Jaruzelski's
visit was a ``massive publicity stunt'' by Polish communist
authorities.
   ``They have lost and he has no right to come here as a
representative of the Polish people,'' said Jarski. ``If he claims
he wants to restore democracy then his first step must be to resign
and have really free elections.''
   Jarski compared Jaruzelski with the communist leaders responsible
for crushing the pro-democracy movement in China.
   ``We have not forgotten that it was Jaruzelski who sent troops to
crush democracy in Poland'' said Jarski, who referred to the killing
of striking ship workers in 1970 at the Gdansk shipyards and the
imposition of martial law in December 1981.
   Solidarity, established during strikes in August 1980, was
suspended under martial law and subsequently outlawed by Parliament.
It was legalized again under an April pact with the government that
opened the way for the elections.
   Jaruzelski's visit is aimed at widening contacts with Western
governments. French President Francois Mitterrand will visit Poland
next week and President Bush will visit Warsaw July 9-11.
   In Sunday's elections for the 100-member Senate Solidarity won 92
seats and eight were undecided and will be determined in runoff
balloting. Opposition and independent candidates were allowed to run
for only 161 seats in the 460-seat Sejm, or lower house, and they
won 160.
   Only two of 35 Communist Party and government candidates who ran
unopposed on a ``national list'' received more than 50 percent of
the vote, which was required for them to win the seats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
