<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-China-Returns     06-10 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Returns,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Returning From Beijing Bring Back Stories Of Turmoil</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA DE LA CRUZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of Americans fleeing Beijing arrived
Saturday with vivid stories of Chinese students carrying corpses in
the street, vehicles on fire and frenzied attempts by foreigners to
escape the military crackdown.
   ``We felt like refugees,'' said Lorene Sheppard of Seattle, who
was on vacation with her mother, Sylvane Drake.
   In Los Angeles, a Chinese graduate student feared arrested
following the bloody crackdown in the Chinese capital arrived
safely, his adviser said.
   ``Getting out of Beijing was a fiasco,'' said Dr. Neil Bryant of
the People to People Ambassador Program upon his arrival at
Seattle-Tacoma International Airport.
   ``At the airport, there was a lot of chaos, a tremendous amount
of confusion,'' the Seattle resident said. ``We were bumped off two
flights.''
   Continental flew three unscheduled charter flights from Beijing
to Tokyo on Saturday, transferring passengers to regular flights out
of Japan.
   Many apparently still felt a sense of urgency even after reaching
Tokyo.
   Passengers pushed through gates, said Capt. John Carl of Everett,
Wash., who piloted Continental Flight 38 from Tokyo to Seattle.
   Thirty-nine Americans who left Beijing were listed on Flight 38,
said Jim Collins, a Continental spokesman in Denver.
   Passenger Lisa Breitenbach was one of 40 Charlotte, N.C.,
residents who traveled to Baoding, China, their community's sister
city.
   The group arrived last Sunday in Beijing, and saw students
carrying corpses on stretchers and countless military vehicles on
fire, Breitenbach said.
   ``We saw people breaking wood to make clubs,'' Sheppard said.
``We were on the 15th floor of the Beijing Hotel, and saw four buses
on fire last Saturday and litters of people in the street.''
   ``It was the saddest thing I've ever seen,'' said Susan Durard,
who is from San Francisco and is with People to People, a non-profit
group of health professionals who bring their medical expertise to
other countries.
   ``We saw people with little babies in their arms, asking the
soldiers to leave them alone,'' Durard said. ``Our guide was a
Chinese doctor and he was crying and crying.''
   Durard said some People to People participants wore black ribbons
to show their support for the students.
   ``There is hatred of the Chinese government everywhere,'' she
said.
   Bryant said that when the group was returning from a trip to the
Great Wall, two lines of troops armed with rifles and bayonets
surrounded their bus.
   The group ``hit the deck,'' he said. ``I didn't know what was
going to happen.''
   Group members made it back to the hotel safely, but were confined
there.
   Breitenbach praised the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, which has been
criticized by some returnees, for doing a ``fantastic'' job
evacuating Americans. Some members of her group have already
returned to the United States, and others waited to come home.
   Bryant said he taped passengers' cheers as his flight left
Beijing for Tokyo.
   ``When those wheels went up, it was great, but it was quite a
tremendous emotional process,'' he said. ``We left behind some
wonderful people. The government is just crushing them.''
   Among the Chinese feared caught in the violence and the arrests
that followed was Tong Boning, a University of California at Los
Angeles graduate student who took $8,000 in donations to
pro-democracy protesters in Beijing.
   The 25-year-old man's last contact with friends in the United
States was last Sunday, when he held his telephone to the window of
his Beijing Hotel room to let a friend hear gunfire.
   Tong was last seen Monday trying to board a flight out of
Beijing. He didn't make it.
   On Saturday morning, he arrived in Los Angeles, said adviser S.Y.
Cheng, head of the UCLA graduate mathematics department.
   ``He is very tired. In a couple of days, we will have a press
conference and talk about it,'' Cheng said by telephone.
</TEXT>
