<FIRST>r a AM-China-StudentLeader     06-10 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Student Leader,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Leader Says Chinese Tanks `Made Pancakes' Out of Protesters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese student leader on Saturday issued an
account of the crackdown against student protests in Beijing a week
ago, saying it was her responsibility to tell the truth being denied
in government reports.
   Cai Ling, who identified herself as the students' chief commander
from June 2 to June 4, said in an audio recording broadcast on the
CBS Evening News on Saturday that many students died and ``the
executioners were the soldiers of the 27th Army.''
   ``I think I'm the most qualified to talk about it, and it's my
responsibility to tell everyone the truth,'' Ms. Ling said through
an interpreter.
   She denied official Chinese government reports that only
soldiers, not students, were killed in Tiananmen Square a week ago.
Then she described the confrontation, saying many of the students
didn't expect violence.
   ``Some students still had hopes in the government and in the
soldiers. They thought, at most, that they would be carried away.
They were tired and returned to their tents to sleep.
   ``Then the tanks made pancakes out of them. ... I don't know the
total (number of dead), but the members of the Independent Workers
Union, on the outside, they stood their ground. And now they're all
dead.
   ``After students left the tanks and all their personnel carriers
flattened the tents with the bodies inside. Then they poured
gasoline over the remains and burned them,'' she said.
   Thousands of students, joined by workers and others, had
virtually paralyzed Chinese government operations in Tiananmen
Square for several weeks before soldiers took back the area on June
3. Estimates of the number of people killed range up to 3,000.
   CBS News said it had obtained the tape recording ``from a secret
location.''
</TEXT>
