<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Hostages     06-10 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Hostages,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Six Foreign Hostages in Lebanon Moved to Iran To Ensure Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Observer newspaper, quoting unidentified
sources, reported Sunday that six Western hostages in Lebanon _ five
Americans and one Briton _ have been moved to Iran to ensure their
safety.
   The weekly identified none of the Americans but said the Briton
was television journalist John McCarthy.
   Quoting unidentified sources in Beirut, Damascus and Tehran, it
said McCarthy and two of the Americans were disguised as injured
Lebanese, transferred to the Syrian capital May 24 and flown to
Tehran.
   The newspaper said three of the seven other Americans abducted by
Iranian-backed Moslem extremists since 1985 were moved to Iran on
May 29.
   The Observer quoted the sources as saying Iran's interior
minister, Ali Akbar Mohtashami, decided to move the hostages after
intensified fighting between Moslems and Christians since March that
has left hundreds of people dead. The newspaper said Mohtashami
``has powerful leverage with Lebanese kidnap gangs.''
   McCarthy, 32, was snatched by gunmen as he headed to Beirut
Airport after five weeks on a Middle East assignment for
London-based Worldwide Television News. The abduction took place two
days after the U.S. bombing raid on Libya. No group claimed
responsibility.
   Altogether 15 Westerners, including nine Americans, are believed
held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists in Lebanon. The
longest-held is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent
for The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
