<HEAD>Brushfires Burning In Carlsbad Caverns Park</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fires consuming at least 650 acres,
quote, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARLSBAD CAVERNS NATIONAL PARK, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters used air
tankers and helicopters Saturday to help battle two blazes in steep
canyon terrain at Carlsbad Caverns National Park, a U.S. Forest
Service spokesman said.
   The larger of the lightning-sparked blazes consumed at least 600
acres of extremely dry desert shrubbery, while the second charred at
least 50 acres, fire information officer John Carpenter said.
   ``Carlsbad Caverns National Park has suspended all backcountry
use within the park,'' Carpenter said. ``But travel is not
restricted into the caverns.''
   About 180 firefighters from the U.S. Bureau of Land Management,
the National Park Service, the Forest Service and the U.S. Bureau of
Indian Affairs were dispatched, in addition to three helicopters and
two air tankers, Carpenter said.
   Firefighters expected to contain both fires by Monday evening, he
said.
   The firefighters found the smaller fire Saturday morning, about
six miles away from the one that started Friday afternoon. It was
the eighth lightning-caused blaze in the park since Thursday evening.
   No injuries were reported, and the fires, about 25 miles
southwest of Carlsbad, did not threaten the cavern's entrances,
elevators or parking lots.
</TEXT>
