<FIRST>r a AM-Pakistan-Nuclear     06-10 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Nuclear,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Has Doubts About Bhutto's Assurances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration believes Pakistan is
pressing ahead with a program to develop nuclear weapons despite its
prime minister's assurances to the contrary, The New York Times
reported in its Sunday editions.
   Unidentified administration officials quoted by the Times praised
Pakistan for slowing some aspects of its atomic program that worry
American analysts. However, they said there has been no slowdown in
other areas, such as Pakistan's longstanding worldwide efforts to
buy parts and nuclear weapons technology.
   Pakistan each year faces the cutoff of American military aid
unless the president certifies that the country does not possess a
nuclear device.
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto told President Bush and Congress
this week that Pakistan did not plan to make an atomic bomb.
   During her meeting with Bush, Central Intelligence Agency
Director William Webster took the unusual step of telling her in
detail what the United States knows about the Pakistani nuclear
program.
   The officials said Bush had decided it was important to show Ms.
Bhutto the extent of the United States' ability to monitor
activities in her country, the Times said.
