<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 2212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EarningsTest     06-10 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earnings Test,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Wants To Up Limits On Earnings By Older Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said Saturday he plans to
introduce legislation that would allow older Americans to earn more
money while holding on to more of their Social Security earnings.
   Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, said his bill
would increase both the amount of earnings a Social Security retiree
can have with no reduction in benefits, as well as reducing the rate
of reduction for those who earn over the limit.
   Under his proposal, a person who earned $15,000 in additional
income over their Social Security benefit would be allowed to retain
almost $800 more in Social Security benefits than under the present
law, said the Texas Democrat.
   Under the current Social Security earnings test, those 70 and
older are eligible for full benefits without regard to earnings.
   But those under 70 are considered retired and eligible for full
benefits only if their earnings are lower than a specified exemption
level.
   In 1990, the maximum a retiree aged 65 to 69 could earn without
suffering a reduction in Social Security benefits will be $9,360
under present law, said Bentsen. He would boost that to $10,620.
   Bentsen said that under his plan a person age 65 to 69, earning
$15,000 and receiving $8,000 in Social Security benefits, would lose
$1,095 in benefits next year, compared with $1,880 under existing
law.
   Retirees now typically lose all benefits when they have earnings
in excess of $34,000. Under the Bentsen plan, a person with $8,000
in Social Security benefits would have to earn almost $36,000 before
losing them all.
   Aides estimated that at least 600,000 Social Security
beneficiaries would benefit from the changes proposed by Bentsen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
