<FIRST>r a AM-HoffmanPicnic     06-10 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hoffman Picnic,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends, Protesters Gather For Hoffman Memorial Picnic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE RULE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON CROSSING, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 people gathered
Saturday at a memorial picnic for activist Abbie Hoffman, but
counter-demonstrators called the event a ``desecration'' of
historical Washington Crossing State Park.
   Among those at the picnic were Black Panther founder Bobby Seale
and poet Allen Ginsberg, who said he had tried to contact Hoffman
about a week before the activist committed suicide April 12 in his
apartment near New Hope.
   The poet, who said he knew Hoffman was depressed because his
mother was ill, recounted leaving a Tibetan saying on Hoffman's
answering machine: ``You will live or you will die. Both are good.''
   Ginsberg read political poems dealing with the Iran-Contra
scandal and environmental issues, then led the crowd in singing Joe
Cocker's song, ``You Are So Beautiful.''
   Seale said the people who called Hoffman un-American and a
dropout were wrong. ``He always said he never considered himself
outside the (political) system,'' Seale said.
   ``His heart, mind and soul could be found in the first two
paragraphs of the Declaration of Independence of the United
States,'' said Seale.
   Two groups staged counter-demonstrations at the park, saying a
memoral service there for Hoffman was a ``desecration'' of the
soldiers buried near the park, where George Washington crossed with
his troops to surprise British soldiers during the battle of Trenton
in 1776.
   Vietnam veteran John Corbett Jr., one of those protesting the
picnic, said Hoffman ``didn't care about anything but Abbie
Hoffman.''
   Hoffman started the Yippie movement to protest the Vietnam War,
then rose to prominence as one of the Chicago Seven, a group of
radicals tried on charges of trying to disrupt the bloody Democratic
National Convention in Chicago in 1968.
   Hoffman's younger brother, Jack, and his mother, Florence,
traveled from Massachusetts for the gathering. ``He would have loved
this,'' the younger Hoffman said. ``He would have loved this spirit
of activism.''
   The activist also would have appreciated the protesters, his
brother said. ``He would have said that's what America's all about.''
   The gathering was sponsored by the environmental group,
Del-AWARE. Hoffman had moved to Pennsylvania to protest the building
of a nuclear power plant in Limerick Township, and to protest the
Point Pleasant pump near the Delaware River.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
