<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Beadle     06-10 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Beadle,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>George Beadle, Nobel Prize-Winning Biologist, Dies at 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POMONA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George W. Beadle, a Nobel Prize-winning
biologist and former president of the University of Chicago, died
after a long illness. He was 85.
   Beadle died Friday at a nursing home in this Southern California
town. Relatives didn't supply the cause of death but said he had
been suffering from Alzheimer's disease, said university spokesman
Jonathan Kleinbard.
   ``George Beadle was an enormously distinguished scientist of
great personal qualities and quiet personal force. He presided over
a very important period of significant growth and enduring renewal
for the University of Chicago,'' said school President Hanna Gray.
   Beadle shared the Nobel Prize in physiology and medicine in 1948
with Edward Tatum and Joshua Lederberg for their discovery that
genes act by controlling enzymes that direct chemical reactions.
   His later studies clarified the origins of domestic corn, and he
was the author of a number of books on genetics.
   He was named president of the University of Chicago in 1961 and
retired in 1968.
   Beadle was born Oct. 22, 1903 on a farm near Wahoo, Neb. He
received his doctorate degree from Cornell University in 1931.
   He taught at Harvard and Stanford universtities and the
California Institute of Technology before coming to Chicago.
   Beadle is survived by his wife Muriel Barnett Beadle of Pomona;
his sister, Ruth; his sons, Redmond Barnett and David Beadle; and
five grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890610-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 2312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-KlanSentence     06-10 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Klan Sentence,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Klan Leader To Probation, Memorization Of Boy Scout
Oath</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Ku Klux Klan leader found guilty of
verbally abusing a police officer was ordered by a State Court judge
to memorize the Boy Scout oath and laws.
   Judge Robert McDuff last week ordered David Lee Craig to serve
six months on probation, pay a $130 fine and memorize the Scout
creed. Craig was found guilty of cursing Acworth Officer D. Barton
while Craig distributed KKK literature on a street last year.
   McDuff ordered Craig, the grand dragon of the True Knights of the
KKK, to memorize ``precepts ... to acquaint you with moral precepts
prevalent in our society.'' The oath and laws were taken from the
Boy Scout creed, he said.
   ``You are not being directed to approve or espouse them, merely
to memorize and know them,'' McDuff said in his order.
   The oath reads: ``On my honor, I will do my best to do my duty to
God and my country and to obey the Scout law, to help other people
at all times, to keep myself physically strong, mentally awake and
morally straight.''
   McDuff said he routinely orders memorization of the pledge of
allegiance to first-time offenders sentenced to probation with no
jail time.
   Craig was arrested Dec. 17 by Barton, who stopped to break up
traffic congestion problems caused by Klan members in Acworth.
</TEXT>
