<FIRST>r a AM-Murder-Suicide     06-10 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder-Suicide,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man May Have Loved Wife Too Much</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 80-year-old man may have been too much
in love with his wife of nearly 60 years, friends and neighbors said
after police discovered the couple dead in a murder-suicide.
   Officials at the Beverly Terrace Nursing Home, where Ella
Streblow moved after suffering a stroke, called police when the
82-year-old woman didn't return from an outing with her husband,
Ewald, Thursday night.
   Later that night, officers found the couple's bodies in the
garage at their home in this city of about 18,000 people about
halfway between Milwaukee and Madison. Mrs. Streblow had been shot
once, and her husband hanged by a rope from the rafters.
   ``I look over there and I just can't believe it,'' said a
neighbor of 30 years, who asked not to be identified by name. ``They
were in love, really. They never did anything separately.''
   Members of Streblow's family visited him Sunday and noticed
nothing amiss, except that he remained depressed about his wife's
condition.
   Nursing home employees also noticed nothing out of the ordinary
when Streblow arrived Thursday to pick up his wife.
   ``It was just another visit,'' said Jean Brennan, who works in
Beverly Terrace's office.
   Mrs. Streblow moved into the nursing home last October when her
husband could no longer care for her at home.
   The Rev. Myron Kell, who knew the couple well, said the warning
signs were present, but no one realized how serious they were.
   ``This man was sinking deeper and deeper into depression because
of his wife's physical condition,'' said the Lutheran minister, the
couple's pastor for the last 20 years. ``He just seemed to be the
kind who withdrew inside of himself.''
   ``He couldn't say two words before he'd start crying,'' the
neighbor of 30 years said.
   Kell, who had visited Streblow weekly in the past month, said the
couple may have been too wrapped up in each other. He said friends,
family and he and his co-pastors tried unsuccessfully to nudge
Streblow out of his depression.
</TEXT>
