<DOCNO> AP890610-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 2325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary     06-10 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists and Opposition Reach Agreement on Election Negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Communist Party and
opposition groups signed an agreement Saturday for negotiations on a
plan to provide for free elections next year and the transition to a
multiparty system.
   ``This offers the hope of a way out of the dead-end Hungarian
society and the hope that we may arrive at free elections which will
open the way to a new democratic Hungary,'' said Peter Toelgyessy, a
spokesman for the opposition organizations.
   The negotiations are to begin Tuesday in the Parliament building
and be televised.
   The agreement, signed by representatives of 17 groups including
the communists that are to take part in the negotiations, ended
months of talks.
   Communist Party Secretary Gyoergy Fejti called the agreement ``an
important milestone.''
   He told a news conference, ``We all agree that we want change.
The competition among us involves who has better ideas, given that
we all wish to avoid social destabilization.''
   Toelgyessy, speaking at the same news conference, said, ``The
talks are aimed solely at a peaceful transition to free elections
which will then reveal the strenth of the various parties.''
   Parliamentary elections are scheculed for mid-1990.
   The negotiations are to be three-sided. Nine opposition groups
have formed an alliance called the Opposition Round Table. The two
other participants will be the Communist Party and a group of
Communist-affiliated organizations.
   One section of the eight-page agreement states: ``The transition
from a one-party system to a representative democracy and the
creation of a constitutional state is realizable only through free
elections.''
   The document specifies that key legislation, such as a planned
law on political parties and drafts of a new constitution, must be
discussed in the negotiations before going to Parliament. Opposition
groups had insisted on that condition.
   The negotiations are to begin only three days before the reburial
ceremony of the remains of Imre Nagy, premier during the 1956 revolt
that was crushed by Soviet forces. Nagy was arrested, convicted of
crimes against the state and executed in 1958. His body was buried
in an unmarked grave.
</TEXT>
