<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Beadle obit; AMs separates moved as a0490 on Lieftinck,
a0529 on Spaggiari; a0551 on Beadle.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>George Beadle</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POMONA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George W. Beadle, a Nobel Prize-winning
biologist and former president of the University of Chicago, died
Friday after a long illness. He was 85.
   Beadle shared the Nobel Prize in physiology and medicine in 1948
with Edward Tatum and Joshua Lederberg for their discovery that
genes act by controlling enzymes that direct chemical reactions.
   His later studies clarified the origins of domestic corn, and he
was the author of a number of books on genetics.
   He was named president of the University of Chicago in 1961 and
retired in 1968. He received his doctorate degree from Cornell
University in 1931. He taught at Harvard and Stanford universtities
and the California Institute of Technology before coming to Chicago.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Albert Spaggiari</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HYERES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Spaggiari, mastermind of the
spectacular 1976 ``sewer gang'' bank heist and on the run for 12
years, died of lung cancer and his body was left at his mother's
house on Saturday. He was 57.
   Spaggiari, who had a photography business in Nice, formed the
gang of ``sewer rats'' who tunneled their way into the Societe
Generale bank in Nice and over the July 17-19 weekend in 1976,
opened 337 safe deposit boxes and made off with gold, jewelry and
negotiable paper worth an estimated $6,835,812.
   Spaggiari was arrested shortly after the break-in but escaped
March 10, 1977. Two books, including Spaggiari's own account, were
written on the exploit and a film was made called ``The Sewers of
Paradise.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Pieter Lieftinck</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pieter Lieftinck, a former Dutch
finance minister and top official of the International Monetary
Fund, died Saturday of heart failure. He was 86.
   Lieftinck, a lifelong member of the Dutch Labor Party, devoted
his career to monetary and tax reform and served as a delegate to
the World Bank and the IMF in Washington from 1956 to 1976.
   He was finance minister from 1945-1952 and oversaw the financial
side of the Netherlands' recovery from the destruction of World War
II. Before the war, Lieftinck was a professor of economics in
Rotterdam.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Evan Aurand</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Vice Adm. Evan Peter Aurand, the first
pilot to land a jet fighter on an aircraft carrier, died Wednesday.
He was 71.
   Aurand, a 1938 graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy, earned the
Navy Cross for a dive-bombing attack on an enemy ship near New
Guinea in 1942. He won a Distinguished Flying Cross commanding the
Navy's first night fighter squadron.
   He made the first jet fighter carrier landing in 1948 aboard the
USS Boxer off San Diego.
   He served as President Eisenhower's naval aide from 1957 to 1961,
and in that capacity was credited with making possible the voyage of
the submarine USS Nautilus under the North Pole ice.
   Aurand was named commander of the Pacific Fleet's Anti-Submarine
Warfare Force in 1969 and in 1972 retired from the Navy.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert Delaney</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert W. Delaney, a Florida Today
political columnist whose career as a newsman spanned 44 years, died
Friday of cancer at age 71.
   Delaney was best known for his coverage of attempts to
desegregate Florida's schools in the 1950s. He joined Florida Today
in 1982 and had worked for Time Inc., The Orlando Sentinel, The
Miami News and several radio and television stations.
   He was survived by his wife Jo Nell, daughter Kay Sloan of
Clearwater, son Robert W. Delaney III of Miami, stepson Charles
Phillips of Jupiter, and stepdaughter Lynn Laikin of Charlotte, N.C..
</TEXT>
