<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 2339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HUD-Contractors     06-10 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Contractors,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: HUD Contractors Embezzled Foreclosure Proceeds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contractors working for the Department of Housing
and Urban Development systematically embezzled millions of dollars
the government should have received from homes sold after
foreclosure, The New York Times reported in its Sunday editions.
   The newspaper said private escrow agents took the money with
little fear of recrimination from the Reagan administration.
   HUD Inspector General Paul A. Adams has been ordered by HUD
Secretary Jack Kemp to conduct investigations in Denver, Houston,
New Orleans, Los Angeles and Washington, the newspaper said.
   ``There are several investigations and-or prosecutions around the
country in which the loss to HUD or the funds allegedly appropriated
to HUD exceed $1 million each,'' said assistant U.S. attorney Gary
P. Jordan of Baltimore, who is handling a Maryland case.
   In that case, an escrow agent, Marilyn Harrell, has been dubbed
``Robin HUD'' by federal investigators because she told agents that
she diverted as much as $5.5 million to charity, the newspaper said.
   The federal investigation, the Times reported, is separate from a
Congressional inquiry into allegations that influence-peddling at
the department allowed more than a dozen former Reagan
administration officials to benefit from housing programs meant for
the poor.
   The Washington Post on Saturday reported that the head of the
housing department's Washington office and three of her assistants
were placed on administrative leave last week pending a review of
charges that Harrell used HUD money to buy 20 homes and 40
automobiles for the poor.
   The Post said senior HUD officials estimated cost to the
government by alleged mismanagement at the Washington office at $10
million.
   ``This could never have gone on if they were doing their jobs
right,'' Harrell told the Times.
   In Texas, the inquiry has led to the indictment of Reba Louise
Lovell, 36, who is accused of embezzling $2.5 million from the sale
of 55 government-owned private homes in the Dallas area.
   The 79-count indictment against Ms. Lovell accused her of trying
to hide her activities by depositing sales proceeds in local banks
in amounts less than $10,000 so that they would not be reported to
the federal government.
   The homes in Texas were sold over a four-month period last year
and sold for between $15,000 to $80,000 each in the Dallas area
including Cedar Hill, Keller, and Fort Worth.
   HUD employs private escrow agents throughout the nation to handle
paperwork and to transfer the money from the sales of private homes
and other government properties to government accounts. The homes
being sold by the government have been obtained because the owners
default on their HUD-insured mortgages.
   After a home is resold, an escrow agent is supposed to transfer
the money to HUD, minus a small commission, often between $50 to
$200, the Times reported.
   In many instances, investigators told the newspaper, HUD
officials failed to notice that the money from the sales was not
transferred.
   One investigator told the Times: ``The laxity of oversight by HUD
was frightening. Nobody noticed, nobody cared, that the money wasn't
coming in. These private agents apparently felt after a while they
had carte blanche to keep it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
