<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Rebels     06-10 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Rebels,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Rebel Leader Among 14 Guerrillas Killed in Gunfight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The No. 3 leader of the Maoist Shining Path
movement was among 14 guerrillas killed by army units in a gun
battle in the southern highlands, the government reported Saturday.
   It said David Orosco, known as Comrade Merino, and the other
rebels were killed when they were trapped by an army unit in a
district in Apurimac state 320 miles southeast of Lima.
   The gunfight occurred Monday but information was delayed because
of the remoteness of the area and checks to identify Orosco as among
those slain, officials reported.
   Army intelligence sources said Orosco and a band of rebels used a
a base camp near the Pampas river in Apurimac to launch attacks
against targets in Apurimac and Ayacucho states. The government made
no mention of army casualties in the battle.
   Osman Morote, considered to be the Shining Path's No. 2 leader,
was captured about a year ago in Lima. He is awaiting trial on
charges of murder and terrorism.
   A tribunal of judges selected to try Morote, fearing attacks
against them by Shining Path assassins, have asked for insurance
policies worth $500,000 and special security measures.
   Abimael Guzman, a former professor of philosophy, is the Shining
Path's main leader.
   The guerrilla group emerged in 1980 and nearly 15,000 people have
been killed in its efforts to overthrow the government, according to
official statistics.
</TEXT>
