<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-China     06-10 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-China,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, in Switch, Focusing on Human Rights in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When President Bush visited China four months
ago, he declined to emphasize human rights issues. Now, faced with
repression there on a grand scale, he is making it a focus of his
China policy.
   Bush told an East Room news conference, ``We have to speak out in
favor of human rights. We aren't going to remake the world, but we
should stand for something.''
   He also defended the U.S. decision to harbor China's most famous
dissident, astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, in the U.S. Embassy in
Beijing, saying ``It's awful hard when a man presents himself, a
person who is a dissident, and says his life is threatened, to turn
him back.''
   ``That isn't one of the premises on which the United States was
founded,'' Bush added at the Thursday night news conference.
   Fang is now enjoying the U.S. hospitality he was unable to claim
last February when he was invited to be a guest of the president at
dinner in Beijing.
   On the final night of a three-day visit to China, Bush hosted a
Texas-style barbecue for Chinese leaders in a Beijing hotel. But
Fang, who has spoken out repeatedly against human-rights abuses in
China, was barred from attending by Chinese police.
   Bush's protests did not come until the next day, amid some foot
shuffling by the administration over who actually invited the
dissident to the U.S.-hosted event _ the White House or the embassy
staff.
   The president's slowness of response in the incident and his
failure to stress the human rights issue _ either in public speeches
or in private meetings with Chinese senior leader Deng Xiaoping and
Prime Minister Li Peng _ drew criticism from some quarters.
   It also evoked comparisons with his predecessor, former President
Reagan, who often used public forums in communist countries to speak
out forcefully on human rights.
   Bush, in part, played down the issue during his visit so as not
to offend top Chinese officials. He has a personal relationship with
many of them. And he also has cited his familiarity with the Chinese
sensitivity to criticism from outside on internal matters.
   However, any constraints Bush may previously have felt about
denouncing human-rights abuses in clear terms were washed away with
the bloodshed of the past week in Tiananmen Square.
   His spokesman said Friday, ``Keep in mind that the government has
murdered many, many of its citizens. We have had an incredible
upheaval in (that) country.''
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater added, ``Things are not going back to
normal soon or in a quick fashion. ... A situation has been put in
effect in China that is going to have an influence on that country
and on their relations with all countries of the world for a
considerable period of time.''
   As for the president, the personal relationships he established
with senior Chinese leaders over the years since he served there as
U.S. envoy in 1974-75 have been of little use to him in the current
crisis.
   As he told his news conference, he put in a call to Chinese
leaders but the line was busy.
   Fitzwater on Friday disclosed that the leader Bush had been
trying to reach was Deng Xiaoping himself. ``We were just informed
the call would not go through,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``The call remains in place ... and of course, now it's public.
I'm sure Chinese officials have read about it and so forth,'' the
spokesman added.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Tom Raum covers the White House for The Associated
Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
