<FIRST>r w PM-US-China     06-10 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Americans Said to Have Fled China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Americans appear to have fled
China during the past week, spurred by the savage crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators and the advice of Secretary of State
James A. Baker III that all U.S. citizens should depart.
   According to figures released Friday by State Department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler, slightly more than 1,500 Americans
remained in the nation of 1 billion.
   U.S. officials had estimated that about 8,800 U.S. citizens were
in the country prior to last week's violence in which hundreds of
demonstrators were killed by Chinese troops.
   Ms. Tutwiler described Beijing as ``still an armed camp.''
   The White House on Friday denounced the Chinese government's call
for reprisals against the demonstrators and stressed that
authorities there had ``murdered many, many of its citizens.''
   President Bush, who placed a call to Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping
earlier in the week but was unable to get through, had not heard
back from Deng by Friday evening.
   ``The phone call remains placed and we'll see if he returns our
call,'' presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   An administration source familiar with intelligence estimates
said the number of Chinese troops in and around the capital city had
grown to about 340,000 from 200,000 estimated earlier in the week.
   Deng appeared in public Friday for the first time since May 16 to
attend a ceremony at which he saluted military leaders for carrying
out the crackdown on the ``counter-revolutionaries'' who had
occupied Beijing's Tiananmen Square until last weekend's military
assault.
   Ms. Tutwiler said Deng's reappearance did not settle the question
of who is in charge in China, nor does it clarify who bears
responsibility for ordering the crackdown.
   ``We think that it's a very clouded situation, and we aren't in a
situation to judge at this time to see who is in charge of what,''
she said. ``To be perfectly honest ... it seems to me that that
would be something the Chinese should be telling us, versus us
trying to sit back and guess.''
   Said Fitzwater: ``You can watch television and see who the
government is, but in terms of individual actions and motivations
... we don't know.''
   But he added that ``I don't think anyone doubts'' that Deng and
Prime Minister Li Peng are now in charge of the overall government
in Beijing.
   Fitzwater used some of the strongest language yet to express U.S.
condemnation of the military actions against unarmed civilians.
   ``Keep in mind that the government has murdered many, many of its
citizens,'' said Fitzwater. ``Things are not going back to normal
soon or in a quick fashion.''
   He noted calls for reprisals were being announced over the
loudspeakers in the public squares in Beijing.
   ``Reprisals are repugnant. We certainly watch this situation with
grave concern,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush suspended military sales to China on Monday but has
refrained from economic sanctions, saying he does not want to cause
hardship for the Chinese people.
   Ms. Tutwiler said Friday there are approximately 500 Americans
left in Beijing, including 150 to 200 journalists and 116 U.S.
Embassy personnel. The remainder are business people and tourists,
she said.
   Between 50 and 100 Amercians are in Tianjin, near Beijing, and
the embassy has organized a bus caravan to return them to the
capital, the spokeswoman said.
   She said 10 dependents of U.S. government personnel are left in
China and will be leaving soon, and no American students remain at
Beijing University, one of the rallying points of the pro-democracy
movement.
</TEXT>
