<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--NavigationSatellite     06-10 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Navigation Satellite,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Launch Attempt Set For Navigation Satellite Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force planned a sixth attempt
to launch an advanced navigation satellite after a thunderstorm
scrubbed the latest try.
   Liftoff was scheduled for a nine-minute period about 6:30 p.m.
today.
   Air Force Lt. Col. Bob Tayloe, the launch director, called off
Friday's effort 30 minutes before the planned liftoff because of a
forecast of lightning within 10 miles of the launch pad. A storm was
moving onto Cape Canaveral at the time.
   The first three launch attempts last month were halted by bad
weather. The fourth ended in a last-second abort when an engine fuel
valve failed to open. The valve has been replaced.
   The Delta 2 rocket is to boost into orbit a $65 million Navstar
satellite designed to enable U.S. and allied military units to fix
their locations anywhere in the world within 50 feet.
</TEXT>
