<HEAD>Rap Star's Arrest Heats Up Philadelphia District Attorney's Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rap star Williard Smith, known to fans as
Fresh Prince, heated up the city's district attorney race after his
lawyer, a contender in the race, groused about his client being
jailed overnight.
   Democratic challenger Walter Phillips, Smith's lawyer, had
criticized the prosecutor's office for allowing a person of Smith's
public stature to be arrested and jailed on the evidence of
``polluted'' witnesses.
   District Attorney Ron Castille responded Thursday by letter to
Phillips and said his opponent tried to influence the office when he
called trying to stop Smith's arrest.
   Smith _ part of the duo D.J. Jazzy Jeff and Fresh Prince _ was
charged with assault for allegedly ordering bodyguard Charles Mack
to ``get'' promoter William Hendricks, 38, during an argument at a
Philadelphia radio station Tuesday. Smith of suburban Philadelphia
was freed on bail Wednesday.
   Mack, 23, who police say punched Hendricks, is still at large.
   Smith and his partner, Jeffrey Townes, won a Grammy Award in
February for their hit, ``Parents Just Don't Understand.''
   ``We don't take into account a person's status in life and give
them any special treatment as he thinks this guy should have had,''
Castille said. ``That is not a fair and impartial application of the
law.''
   The district attorney further said he thought it was
inappropriate for Phillips to take cases during an election campaign.
   Phillips said he is not actively seeking clients while running
for office, but Smith's case was referred to him by a friend in New
York.
</TEXT>
