<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Dom DeLuise not only writes about
food, cooks it, grows it and bags it on TV commercials, but he's
co-starring with it on the stage.
   DeLuise plays Public Opinion in a fantasy version of the satiric
light opera ``Orpheus in the Underworld'' by Jacques Offenbach. In
the show, heaven's residents tire of eating and drinking ambrosia.
   ``Mercury goes to hell _ he says the food is gorgeous, they have
sausages and eggs, so there's a revolt,'' DeLuise said recently.
   The sausages and eggs go on to perform a musical number.
   ``There are no holds barred,'' said the portly comedian of the
production, based on the myth about a man who follows his beloved
wife to the underworld in an attempt to rescue her.
   DeLuise, featured in TV commercials for plastic food bags, has
written an autobiographical cookbook, ``Eat This ... It'll Make You
Feel Better.''
   ``Orpheus in the Underworld,'' directed by Peter Mark Schifter,
will run through July 2 at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion of the
Music Center.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica Hahn, who volunteered to lead the
annual Do-Dah Day parade of costumed pets and owners, says it's no
surprise that some animal lovers are angered by her participation in
the event.
   ``Wherever I go in the country, it's like, `You're going to
hell,''' said Ms. Hahn, whose disclosure of her sexual tryst with
evangelist Jim Bakker brought down the PTL leader. ``But, you know,
God doesn't pick sides.''
   A group of Birmingham advertising and broadcasting executives are
sponsoring today's parade, which benefits the Birmingham Humane
Society.
   Humane Society Director Hack Lloyd said he received about a
half-dozen irate calls from pet lovers telling him that Ms. Hahn was
immoral.
   ``I tell them we didn't have anything to do with it, except we're
thrilled to be getting the money,'' Lloyd said.
