<TEXT>
   Singer Stevie Wonder, receiving an award
from the Hungarian Peace Council for ``promoting human
understanding,'' called on people around the world to ``soothe''
each other.
   The blind soul superstar told reporters Friday he didn't think
music could change the world, but people might.
   ''If it's true that music soothes the savage beasts, then if we
are beasts, let's soothe each other. And if we can make the world
better, then obviously we got a job to do,'' said Wonder.
   Wonder also took the opportunity to predict the trend in music in
the next decade.
   ''In the '70s there was disco, some ballads and the beginning of
the appreciation of reggae music,'' he said. ''In the '80s, you got
a combination of a lot of what happened in the '50s, '60s and '70s.
In the '90s, I think we're going to see more international
appreciation of various music.''
   Friday's show at Budapest's Sports Palace was sold out.
