<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Uprising     06-10 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Uprising,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis, Palestinians Face Divisions After 18 Months of Rebellion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Internal divisions among Palestinians and
Israelis have been magnified by 18 months of bloodshed in the
occupied lands and threaten to paralyze peace efforts.
   Leaders on both sides predict that, unless political progress is
made soon, the violence will grow and destroy a historic opportunity
for Arab-Israeli negotiations.
   ``We are at a turning point, either to get a political solution
or resort to more violence,'' said Said Kanaan, a Palestinian
businessman who supports the Palestine Liberation Organization. ``We
are waiting to see if we can reap all that we have planted in the
past 18 months.''
   At least 512 Palestinians have been killed and more than 8,000
wounded in the uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which began its 19th month Friday. Twenty-two Israelis have been
slain.
   Both societies have been polarized and advocates of violence are
becoming more active.
   Palestinian militants insist only a violent struggle can lead to
their own independent state.
   ``We are exposed to a lot of pressure to resort to violent
means,'' Kanaan told The Associated Press. ``This is growing mainly
among the lower cadres of the PLO and the population because the
Israelis are pushing us so much against the wall.''
   On the Israeli side, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir speaks of
harsher measures to crush the uprising and Jewish settlers are
attacking Palestinian villages. A 13-year-old girl was killed in a
recent raid.
   Leftists, by contrast, grow more vocal in demands for talks with
the PLO and formation of a Palestinian state, both taboo in Israel.
   Amos Oz, a prominent leftist writer, said extremism, including
vigilante attacks by settlers, could destroy Israel.
   ``We don't want the nation to be ripped apart, but under no
circumstances will we acquiesce in the transformation of our country
into a monster,'' he told an audience of peace activists.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said in a telephone
interview: ``If both sides lose control completely, the situation
can deteriorate and we can have more violence.''
   Shamir faces increasing pressure in his conservative Likud bloc
to abandon plans for elections in the occupied lands that would
choose Palestinian delegates to negotiate with Israel.
   Shamir has said he will resign if Likud rejects the plan at its
convention next month.
   Mainstream PLO officials have conditionally accepted the
elections as a first step toward negotiating a permanent settlement,
but militants reject any compromise.
   ``I think only the continuation of the uprising will bring us
liberation,'' said Sufian Khatib, a Jerusalem physician whose views
have been linked to those of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, a radical pro-Syrian faction of the PLO.
   ``The only obstacles are the compromises the PLO leadership is
making,'' he said. ``The PLO must focus its efforts only on the
uprising and its continuation.''
   Moderates say the uprising is a means of forcing Israel to
negotiate. Israel has refused contact with the PLO, which it defines
as a terrorist organization.
   ``Israel will find no alternative but to talk with the PLO,''
said Faisal Husseini, a moderate from Arab east Jerusalem. ``Israel
will be forced to approach us as a people with a leadership and
rights.''
   Yossi Ahimeir, a close aide to Shamir, said Israel would not bow
to violence and would crush the rebellion.
   ``The Arabs have two alternatives: to continue with the uprising
or enter the circle of peace,'' he said. ``They will achieve nothing
through the uprising.''
   Liel, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, said: ``If they reject
elections, I don't see in the future any plan that will pull us out
of the circle of violence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
