<FIRST>r w PM-US-Indonesia     06-10 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Indonesia,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Indonesia's Economic Progress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One name for Suharto is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush praised Indonesia's management
of its foreign debt during a brief meeting with the president of the
Southeast Asian nation.
   During a half-hour talk with President Suharto late Friday, Bush
``praised Indonesia's debt management as an example of the
government's sound economic policies,'' the White House sai.
   World Bank headquarters in Washington said the Suharto
government's economic adjustment process ``has already benefited the
(Indonesian) economy, as shown by strong export performance, a
resurgence of investment and economic recovery.''
   The World Bank also announced a new $350 million World Bank loan
to help finance essential imports during the economic adjustment
process.
   The adjustments include encouraging the private sector through
improved incentives and deregulation, the Bank said. A major element
of Suharto's economic program has been to diversify Indonesian
exports away from petroleum so as to insulate the economy from
fluctuating oil prices.
   Suharto and Bush discussed the Cambodian conflict and conditions
generally in Southeast Asia, the White House said. The president
restated goals of self-determination and verified withdrawal of
Vietnamese forces from Cambodia and urged greater two-way
U.S.-Indonesian trade and investment.
</TEXT>
