<FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-89 0139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Morgan-Custody     06-10 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morgan-Custody,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Prosecutor Faces Contempt, Job Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecutor whose sister was jailed
for not revealing the whereabouts of her daughter has defied a judge
by refusing to answer 26 questions about the child.
   The judge, who jailed Elizabeth Morgan in 1987, threatened
Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert M. Morgan with contempt Friday and
said he could be jailed unless he agrees to answer.
   District of Columbia Judge Herbert B. Dixon Jr. excused Robert
Morgan from the courtroom with a warning to report any change of
address or employment.
   Morgan could face professional sanctions, including loss of his
job and disbarrment, for his defiance of the judge's order to answer
questions put to him by Eric A. Foretich, whom Ms. Morgan has
accused of sexually abusing their daughter Hilary.
   Dixon has kept the woman in jail since she sent the 6-year-old
girl into hiding rather than allow the father another court-ordered
visit.
   The custody battle between Ms. Morgan and Foretich, who adamantly
denies abusing the child and contends Ms. Morgan is insane, has been
going on almost since the girl's birth in 1983.
   The hearing Friday was ordered by the District of Columbia Court
of Appeals to determine if continued coercion would ever get Ms.
Morgan to reveal where the child is.
   Robert Morgan's first refusal came when he was asked the
whereabouts of his parents, who disappeared around the time the
child was last seen publicly.
   ``Your honor, I have appeared before most of the judges of the
court, and I have the greatest respect for its jurisdiction,'' he
said. ``But I respectfully decline to answer that question which
could lead to the discovery of my niece or further harm to her.''
   Warned by Dixon that he faced contempt charges, Morgan said, ``My
answer is the same.''
   Ms. Morgan also testified, repeating her contention that she
would remain in jail for the rest of her life rather than produce
the child.
</TEXT>
