<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, U.S. Jews have set aside a special
matzo each Passover and prayed for the emigration of their brethren
in the Soviet Union.
   Now that those prayers have been answered for many, Jews in the
United States are being asked to set aside something more than
unleavened bread _ the money required to resettle as many as 50,000
Jews who are expected to leave the Soviet Union this year.
   The United Jewish Appeal, the national fund-raising campaign for
Jewish causes in the United States and Israel, has launched Passage
to Freedom, an effort aimed at raising $75 million for Soviet
emigres this year.
   Half will go to resettlement activities in the United States. The
rest will be split between Soviet Jews in transit to the United
States, and those seeking to settle in Israel.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio talk show hosts proved they're a force to be
reckoned with during the congressional pay-raise brouhaha, deluging
Capitol Hill with millions of tea bags from angry listeners. But
they still feel ignored.
   So they're meeting in Boston this weekend to do what other
aggrieved minorities do: unite to demand more power.
   ``In the words of Rodney Dangerfield, `We don't get no
respect,''' said organizer Jerry Williams of Boston radio station
WRKO. ``The national media ... never took us very seriously. They
think there's some conspiracy here.''
   About 50 of the country's 225 radio talk show hosts began
arriving Friday for the inaugural TalkRadio Conference, a two-day
gab confab expected to include consumer activist Ralph Nader, TV
talk show host Morton Downey Jr. and political columnist Jack
Anderson.
</TEXT>
